l Report of the National Construction Safety Team on the Collapses of the World Trade Center Tower (NIST NCSTAR 1)|url=http://ws680.nist.gov/publication/get_pdf.cfm?pub_id=909017 |series=Federal Building and Fire Safety Investigation of the World Trade Center Disaster |publisher=National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST) |format=PDF |date=September 2005 |ref={{harvid|NIST NCSTAR 1|2005}}}}\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|World Trade Center (1970\u20132001)}}\n* [http://www.wtc.com/ World Trade Center] \u2013 Silverstein Properties\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/19970419124808/http://www.panynj.gov:80/wtc/wtcfram.HTM World Trade Center (1997)] - [https://web.archive.org/web/20010809130651/http://www.panynj.gov/wtc/wtcmain.HTM World Trade Center (2001)] \u2013 Port Authority of New York & New Jersey\n* {{Dmoz|Regional/North_America/United_States/New_York/Localities/N/New_York_City/Manhattan/Arts_and_Entertainment/Architecture/World_Trade_Center/|World Trade Center}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20100619233331/http://www.life.com/image/first/in-gallery/33502/building-the-twin-towers-a-tribute Building the Twin Towers: A Tribute] \u2013 slideshow by ''[[Life (magazine)|Life]]'' magazine\n* [https://www.pbs.org/wnet/newyork/index.html New York: A Documentary film] features the construction and destruction of the World Trade Center in the seventh and final episode of the series directed by [[Ric Burns]].\n* [http://www.criticalpast.com/video/65675023511_World-Trade-Center_steel-workers_tower-under-construction_John-McCeever Historic video with scenes of World Trade Center under construction in 1970]\n* {{HABS |survey=NY-6369 |id=ny2014 |title=World Trade Center Site |photos=103 |data=21 |cap=8}}\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{S-ach|rec}}\n{{S-bef|rows=5|before=[[Empire State Building]]}}\n{{S-ttl|title=[[List of tallest buildings in the world|Tallest building in the world]]|years=1970\u20131974}} <small>(North Tower)</small>\n{{S-aft|rows=3|after=[[Willis Tower]]}}\n{{S-break}}\n{{S-ttl|title=[[List of tallest buildings in the United States|Tallest building in the United States]]|years=1970\u20131974}} <small>(North Tower)</small>\n{{S-break}}\n{{S-ttl|title=Tallest building with the most floors|years=1970\u20132001}}\n{{S-break}}\n{{S-ttl|title=[[List of tallest buildings in New York City|Tallest building in New York City]]|years=1970\u20132001}} <small>(North Tower)</small>\n{{S-aft|rows=|after=Empire State Building}}\n{{S-break}}\n{{S-ttl|title=Tallest building with the most floors ever|years=1970\u20132008}}\n{{S-aft|rows=|after=[[Burj Khalifa]]}}\n{{S-break}}\n{{S-bef|rows=|before=[[City National Plaza]]}}\n{{S-ttl|title=Tallest twin towers in the world|years=1970\u20131998}}\n{{S-aft|rows=|after=[[Petronas Towers]]}}\n\n{{S-end}}\n\n{{World Trade Center}}\n{{September 11 attacks}}\n{{navboxes|list=\n{{Manhattan}}\n{{PANYNJ navbox}}\n{{Buildings in New York City timeline}}\n{{Supertall skyscrapers|former}}\n{{Minoru Yamasaki}}\n}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:World Trade Center (1973-2001)}}\n[[Category:World Trade Center| ]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures destroyed in the September 11 attacks]]\n[[Category:Buildings associated with crimes]]\n[[Category:Demolished buildings and structures in New York City]]\n[[Category:Destroyed landmarks in New York City]]\n[[Category:Financial District, Manhattan]]\n[[Category:Former skyscrapers]]\n[[Category:Former world's tallest buildings]]\n[[Category:Historic American Buildings Survey in New York City]]\n[[Category:History of New York City]]\n[[Category:Skyscraper office buildings in Manhattan]]\n[[Category:Port Authority of New York and New Jersey]]\n[[Category:Twin towers]]\n[[Category:World Trade Centers|New York]]\n[[Category:Minoru Yamasaki buildings]]\n[[Category:Modernist architecture in New York City]]\n[[Category:Articles containing video clips]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use American English|date=August 2019}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=August 2019}}\n{{Short description|Former skyscraper complex in Manhattan, New York}}\n{{pp-vandalism|small=yes}}\n{{About|the World Trade Center building complex prior to the September 11 attacks|the current buildings|World Trade Center (2001\u2013present)}}\n{{good article}}\n{{Infobox building\n| name               = World Trade Center\n| image              = World Trade Center, New York City - aerial view (March 2001).jpg\n| image_size         = 300px\n| caption            = The original complex in March 2001. The tower on the left, with antenna spire, was [[One World Trade Center#Original building (1970\u20132001)|1&nbsp;WTC]]. The tower on the right was [[2 World Trade Center#Original building (1973\u20132001)|2&nbsp;WTC]]. All seven buildings of the WTC complex are partially visible. The red granite-clad building left of the Twin Towers was the original [[7 World Trade Center]]. In the background is the [[East River]].\n| status             = Destroyed\n| highest_prev       = [[Empire State Building]]\n| highest_next       = [[Willis Tower]]\n| highest_start      = 1970\n| highest_end        = 1973\n| location           = [[Lower Manhattan]], [[New York City]]\n| map_type           = <!--Lower Manhattan#Manhattan#New York City#New York#USA-->\n| coordinates        = {{coord|40|42|42|N|74|00|45|W|region:US-NY|display=inline,title}}\n| floor_count         = {{unbulleted list\n  |1 and 2 WTC: 110 floors\n  |3 WTC: 22 floors\n  |4 and 5 WTC: 9 floors\n  |6 WTC: 8 floors\n  |7 WTC: 47 floors\n  }}\n| start_date         = {{unbulleted list\n |1 WTC: August 6, 1968\n |2 WTC: January 1969\n |3 WTC: March 1979\n |4, 5, and 6 WTC: 1970\n |7 WTC: October 2, 1984\n }}\n| topped_out_date    = {{unbulleted list\n  |1 WTC: December 23, 1970\n  |2 WTC: July 19, 1971\n}} \n| completion_date    = {{unbulleted list\n  |1 WTC: 1972\n  |2 WTC: 1973\n  |3 WTC: April 1, 1981\n  |4 WTC: 1975\n  |5/6 WTC: 1973\n  |7 WTC: 1987\n  }}\n| groundbreaking_date = {{start date and age|August 5, 1966}}\n| opening            = {{unbulleted list\n  |1 WTC: December 15, 1970\n  |2 WTC: September 1971\n  |3 WTC: July 1, 1981<ref>{{cite web|title=The city's newest hotel, the Vista International, officially opened...|url=https://www.upi.com/Archives/1981/07/01/The-citys-newest-hotel-the-Vista-International-officially-opened/3315362808000/|publisher=UPI|date=July 1, 1981|accessdate=May 23, 2018}}</ref>\n  |4 WTC: January 1977\n  |5/6 WTC: 1973\n  |7 WTC: May 1987\n}}\n| inauguration_date    = {{start date and age|April 4, 1973}}\n| destruction_date   = [[September 11 attacks|{{start date and age|2001|09|11}}]]\n| owner              = [[Port Authority of New York and New Jersey]]\n{{collapsed infobox section begin|Other information}}\n| antenna_spire      = 1 WTC: {{convert|1,728|ft|m|1}}\n| roof               ={{unbulleted list\n| '''added_to_NRHP'''= '''May 25, 1993'''\n  |1 WTC: {{convert|1,368|ft|m|1}}\n  |2 WTC: {{convert|1,362|ft|m|1}}\n  |3 WTC: {{convert|250|ft|m|1}}\n  |4 and 5 WTC: {{convert|120|ft|m|1}}\n  |6 WTC: {{convert|110|ft|m|1}}\n  |7 WTC: {{convert|610|ft|m|1}}\n  }}\n| top_floor          = {{unbulleted list\n  |1 WTC: {{convert|1,355|ft|m}}\n  |2 WTC: {{convert|411|m|ft|0|order=flip|abbr=on}}\n  }}\n| floor_area =        {{unbulleted list\n  |1 and 2 WTC: {{convert|4300000|sqft|m2|-4|abbr=on}} each\n  |[[Four World Trade Center|4]], [[Five World Trade Center|5]], and [[Six World Trade Center|6 WTC]]: {{convert|500000|sqft|m2|-4|abbr=on}} each\n  |[[7 World Trade Center|7 WTC]]: {{convert|1868000|sqft|m2|-4|abbr=on}}\n  }}\n| elevator_count           = 1 and 2 WTC: 99 each\n{{collapsed infobox section end}}\n| architectural_style = [[Structural expressionism]]\n| architect                = {{unbulleted list\n  |[[Minoru Yamasaki]]\n  |[[Emery Roth & Sons]]\n  }}\n| engineer                 = [[Magnusson Klemencic Associates|Worthington, Skilling, Helle & Jackson]],<ref>{{cite news |url=http://community.seattletimes.nwsource.com/archive/?date=19930227&slug=1687698 |title=Twin Towers Engineered To Withstand Jet Collision |agency=[[Seattle Times]] |date=February 27, 1993 |access-date=March 11, 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110710023431/http://community.seattletimes.nwsource.com/archive/?date=19930227&slug=1687698 |archive-date=July 10, 2011 |url-status=live}}</ref> [[Leslie E. Robertson|Leslie E. Robertson Associates]]\n| main_contractor               = [[Tishman Realty & Construction|Tishman Realty & Construction Company]]\n| developer                = [[Port Authority of New York and New Jersey]]\n| references               = I. {{note|talleststatus}}{{Emporis |id=131020 |name=World Trade Center}}<br /><ref>{{emporis|131020}}</ref><ref name=\"PANYNJ\"/>\n}}\n\nThe original '''World Trade Center''' was a large complex of seven buildings in the [[Financial District, Manhattan|Financial District]] of [[Lower Manhattan]], [[New York City]], United States. It opened on April 4, 1973, and was destroyed in 2001 during the [[September 11 attacks]]. At the time of their completion, the '''Twin Towers'''\u2014the original [[One World Trade Center#Original building|1 World Trade Center]], at {{convert|1368|ft|m}}; and [[Two World Trade Center#Original building|2 World Trade Center]], at {{convert|1,362|ft|m|1}}\u2014were the [[History of the tallest buildings in the world#Tallest buildings (from 1901)|tallest buildings]] in the world. Other buildings in the complex included the [[Marriott World Trade Center]] (3 WTC), [[Four World Trade Center|4 WTC]], [[Five World Trade Center|5 WTC]], [[Six World Trade Center|6 WTC]], and [[7 World Trade Center|7 WTC]]. The complex contained {{convert|13400000|sqft|m2}} of office space.\n\nThe core complex was built between 1966 and 1975, at a cost of $400&nbsp;million (equivalent to $2.27 billion in 2018<!--${{Format price|{{Inflation|US-GDP|0.4|1971|r=2}}}} billion in {{Inflation-year|US-GDP}}-->).{{Inflation-fn|US-GDP}} During its existence, the World Trade Center experienced several major incidents, including a fire on {{Nowrap|February 13}}, 1975,<ref name=\"nyt 19750214\"/> a [[1993 World Trade Center bombing|bombing]] on {{Nowrap|February 26}}, 1993,<ref name=\"reeve p10\"/> and [[1998 Bank of America robbery|a bank robbery]] on {{Nowrap|January 14}}, 1998.<ref name=\"mafia 2007\"/> In 1998, the [[Port Authority of New York and New Jersey]] decided to privatize it by leasing the buildings to a private company to manage. It awarded the lease to [[Silverstein Properties]] in {{Nowrap|July 2001}}.<ref name=\"cuozzo\"/>\n\nOn [[September 11 attacks|the morning of September 11, 2001]], [[Al-Qaeda]]-affiliated [[Aircraft hijacking|hijackers]] flew two [[Boeing 767]] jets into the North and South Towers within minutes of each other; two hours later, [[Collapse of the World Trade Center|both towers collapsed]]. The attacks killed 2,606 people in and within the vicinity of the towers, as well as all 157 on board the two aircraft.<ref name=\"Borg\">{{cite news |url=http://www.nydailynews.com/ny_local/2011/06/18/2011-06-18_manhattan_mans_death_brings_wtc_toll_to_2753.html |title=Man's death from World Trade Center dust brings Ground Zero toll to 2,753 |date=June 18, 2011 |newspaper=NY Daily News |accessdate=September 1, 2011 |agency=Associated Press}}</ref> Falling debris from the towers, combined with fires that the debris initiated in several surrounding buildings, led to the partial or complete collapse of all the buildings in the complex, and caused catastrophic damage to ten other large structures in the surrounding area.\n\nThe [[Rescue and recovery effort after the September 11 attacks|cleanup and recovery process]] at the [[World Trade Center site]] took eight months, during which the remains of the other buildings were demolished. A new [[World Trade Center (2001\u2013present)|World Trade Center complex]] is being built with six new skyscrapers and several other buildings, many of which are complete. A [[National September 11 Memorial & Museum|memorial and museum]] to those killed in the attacks, a new [[World Trade Center (PATH station)|rapid transit hub]], and an [[Liberty Park|elevated park]] have been opened. [[One World Trade Center]], the tallest building in the Western Hemisphere at {{convert|1776|ft|m}} and the lead building for the new complex, was completed in November 2014.\n\nDuring its existence, the World Trade Center was an icon of New York City.{{sfnp|Gillespie|1999|p=162}} It had a major role in [[World Trade Center in popular culture|popular culture]] and according to one estimate was depicted in 472 films. Following the World Trade Center's destruction, mentions of the complex were altered or deleted, and several dozen \"memorial films\" were created.{{sfnp|Langmead|2009|p=353}}\n\n==Before the World Trade Center==\n[[File:Radio Row-Berenice Abbott.jpg|thumb|left|[[Radio Row]] in 1936, with the [[Cortlandt Street (IRT Ninth Avenue Line)|Cortlandt Street]] station in the background]]\n===Site===\nThe western portion of the World Trade Center site was originally under the [[Hudson River]]. The shoreline was in the vicinity of Greenwich Street, which is closer to the site's eastern border. It was on this shoreline, close to the intersection of Greenwich and the former Dey Street, that Dutch explorer [[Adriaen Block]]'s ship, ''[[Tyger (ship)|Tyger]]'', burned to the waterline in November 1613, stranding him and his crew and forcing them to overwinter on the island. They built the first European settlement in [[Manhattan]]. The remains of the ship were buried under landfill when the shoreline was extended beginning in 1797 and were discovered during excavation work in 1916. The remains of a second eighteenth century ship were discovered in 2010 during excavation work at the site. The ship, believed to be a Hudson River [[sloop]], was found just south of where the Twin Towers stood, about {{Convert|20|feet|m}} below the surface.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://articles.cnn.com/2010-07-15/us/new.york.ground.zero.ship_1_ship-archaeologist-ground-zero?_s=PM:US |title=CNN: Pieces of ship made in 1700s found at ground zero building site |publisher=[[CNN]] |accessdate=October 4, 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110113070306/http://articles.cnn.com/2010-07-15/us/new.york.ground.zero.ship_1_ship-archaeologist-ground-zero?_s=PM%3AUS |archivedate=January 13, 2011 }}</ref>\n\nLater, the area became New York City's [[Radio Row]], which existed from 1921 to 1966. The neighborhood was a [[warehouse district]] in what is now [[Tribeca]] and the [[Financial District, Manhattan|Financial District]]. Harry Schneck opened City Radio on Cortlandt Street in 1921, and eventually the area held several blocks of electronics stores, with Cortlandt Street as its central axis. The used radios, war surplus electronics (e.g., [[AN/ARC-5]] radios), junk, and parts were often piled so high they would spill out onto the street, attracting collectors and scroungers. According to a business writer, it also was the origin of the electronic component distribution business.<ref>{{cite book |title=Ruthless Execution: What Business Leaders Do When Their Companies Hit the Wall |first=Amir |last=Hartman |publisher=[[Financial Times]] [[Prentice Hall]] |location=Upper Saddle River, NJ |year=2004 |isbn=978-0-13-101884-6 |page=[https://archive.org/details/ruthlessexecutio0000hart/page/167 167] |url=https://archive.org/details/ruthlessexecutio0000hart/page/167 }}</ref>\n\n===Establishment of World Trade Center===\nThe idea of establishing a World Trade Center in New York City was first proposed in 1943. The [[New York State Legislature]] passed a bill authorizing New York Governor [[Thomas E. Dewey]] to begin developing plans for the project,<ref name=\"nyt-07061946\">{{cite news |url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1946/07/07/93133680.pdf |title=Dewey Picks Board for Trade Center |work=[[The New York Times]] |language=en-US |issn=0362-4331 |date=July 6, 1946}}</ref> but the plans were put on hold in 1949.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1949/03/11/84200275.pdf |title=Lets Port Group Disband, State Senate for Dissolution of World Trade Corporation |work=The New York Times |language=en-US |issn=0362-4331 |date=March 11, 1949}}</ref> During the late 1940s and 1950s, economic growth in New York City was concentrated in [[Midtown Manhattan]]. To help stimulate [[urban renewal]] in Lower Manhattan, [[David Rockefeller]] suggested that the Port Authority build a World Trade Center there.{{sfnp|Gillespie|1999|pp=32\u201333}}\n\nPlans for the use of [[Eminent domain in the United States|eminent domain]] to remove the shops in Radio Row bounded by [[Vesey Street (Manhattan)|Vesey]], [[Church Street (Manhattan)|Church]], [[Liberty Street (Manhattan)|Liberty]], and [[West Street (Manhattan)|West]] Streets began in 1961 when the [[Port Authority of New York and New Jersey]] was deciding to build the world's first [[List of World Trade Centers|world trade center]]. They had two choices: the east side of [[Lower Manhattan]], near the [[South Street Seaport]]; or the west side, near the [[Hudson and Manhattan Railroad]] (H&M) station, [[Hudson Terminal]].{{sfnp|Glanz|Lipton|2003|p=56}} Initial plans, made public in 1961, identified a site along the [[East River]] for the World Trade Center.{{sfnp|Gillespie|1999|pp=34\u201335}} As a bi-state agency, the Port Authority required approval for new projects from the governors of both [[New York (state)|New York]] and [[New Jersey]]. New Jersey Governor [[Robert B. Meyner]] objected to New York getting a $335&nbsp;million project.{{sfnp|Gillespie|1999|p=38}} Toward the end of 1961, negotiations with outgoing New Jersey Governor Meyner reached a stalemate.<ref name=\"nyt-1961dec29\" />\n\nAt the time, ridership on New Jersey's H&M Railroad had declined substantially from a high of 113&nbsp;million riders in 1927 to 26&nbsp;million in 1958 after new automobile tunnels and bridges had opened across the Hudson River.{{sfnp|Cudahy|2002|p=56}} In a {{Nowrap|December 1961}} meeting between Port Authority director [[Austin J. Tobin]] and newly elected New Jersey Governor [[Richard J. Hughes]], the Port Authority offered to take over the H & M Railroad. They also decided to move the World Trade Center project to the Hudson Terminal building site on the west side of Lower Manhattan, a more convenient location for New Jersey commuters arriving via [[PATH (rail system)|PATH]].<ref name=\"nyt-1961dec29\">{{cite news |url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1961/12/29/119434880.pdf |title=Port Unit Backs Linking of H&M and Other Lines |last=Grutzner |first=Charles |work=The New York Times |language=en-US |issn=0362-4331 |date=December 29, 1961}}</ref> With the new location and the Port Authority's acquisition of the H&M Railroad, New Jersey agreed to support the World Trade Center project.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1962/01/23/102744546.pdf |title=2 States Agree on Hudson Tubes and Trade Center |last=Wright |first=George Cable |date=January 23, 1962 |work=The New York Times |language=en-US |issn=0362-4331}}</ref> As part of the deal, the Port Authority renamed the H&M \"Port Authority Trans-Hudson\", or PATH for short.{{sfnp|Glanz|Lipton|2003|p=59}}\n\nTo compensate Radio Row business owners for their displacement, the Port Authority gave each business $3,000, without regard to how long the business had been there or how prosperous it was.{{sfnp|Glanz|Lipton|2003|p=68}} The Port Authority began purchasing properties in the area for the World Trade Center by March 1965,<ref name=\"nyt 19650329\"/> and demolition of Radio Row began in March 1966.{{sfnp|Gillespie|1999|p=61}} It was completely demolished by the end of the year.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.npr.org/programs/lnfsound/stories/020603.radiorow.html |title='Radio Row:' The neighborhood before the World Trade Center |accessdate=October 1, 2006 |date=June 3, 2002 |publisher=[[National Public Radio]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20061018014921/http://www.npr.org/programs/lnfsound/stories/020603.radiorow.html |archive-date=October 18, 2006 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nApproval was also needed from New York City Mayor [[John Lindsay]] and the [[New York City Council]]. Disagreements with the city centered on tax issues. On {{Nowrap|August 3}}, 1966, an agreement was reached whereby the Port Authority would make annual [[Payment in lieu of taxes|payments to the City in lieu of taxes]] for the portion of the World Trade Center leased to private tenants.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1966/08/04/82499585.pdf |title=City Ends Fight with Port Body on Trade Center |last=Smith |first=Terence |date=August 4, 1966 |work=The New York Times |language=en-US |issn=0362-4331}}</ref> In subsequent years, the payments would rise as the [[Property tax|real estate tax]] rate increased.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1967/01/26/82577347.pdf |title=Mayor Signs Pact on Trade Center |last=Smith |first=Terence |work=The New York Times |language=en-US |issn=0362-4331 |date=January 26, 1967}}</ref>\n\n==Design, construction, and criticism==\n{{Main|Construction of the World Trade Center}}\n\n===Design===\n[[File:World trade center.ogv|thumb|thumbtime=0:57|Video of the World Trade Center in the 1970s, including scenes of its construction|left]]\nOn {{Nowrap|September 20}}, 1962, the Port Authority announced the selection of [[Minoru Yamasaki]] as lead architect and [[Emery Roth|Emery Roth & Sons]] as associate architects.<ref>{{Cite news |title=Architect Named for Trade Center |last=Esterow |first=Milton |date=September 21, 1962 |work=The New York Times |language=en-US |issn=0362-4331|url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1962/09/21/83523078.pdf}}</ref> Yamasaki devised the plan to incorporate twin towers. His original plan called for the towers to be 80 stories tall,<ref name=\"nyt-1964jan19a\"/> but to meet the Port Authority's requirement for {{convert|10000000|sqft|m2}} of office space, the buildings would each have to be 110 stories tall.{{sfnp|Gillespie|1999|p=49}}\n\nYamasaki's design for the World Trade Center, unveiled to the public on {{Nowrap|January 18}}, 1964, called for a square plan approximately {{convert|208|ft|m}} in dimension on each side.<ref name=\"nyt-1964jan19a\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1964/01/19/archives/news-analysis-a-new-era-heralded-architectural-virtue-of-trade.html?searchResultPosition=1 |title=A New Era Heralded |last=Huxtable |first=Ada Louise |work=The New York Times |language=en-US |issn=0362-4331 |date=January 19, 1964 |author-link=Ada Louise Huxtable}}</ref>{{sfnp|NIST NCSTAR 1-1|2005|p=7}} The buildings were designed with narrow office windows {{convert|18|in|cm}} wide, which reflected Yamasaki's [[Acrophobia|fear of heights]] as well as his desire to make building occupants feel secure.<ref name=\"pekala\">{{Cite news |title=Profile of a lost landmark; World Trade Center |publisher=[[Journal of Property Management]] |date=November 1, 2001 |last=Pekala |first=Nancy}}</ref> His design included building facades sheathed in aluminum-alloy.<ref name=\"nyt-1966may29\">{{Cite news |title=Who's Afraid of the Big Bad Buildings |last=Huxtable |first=Ada Louise |date=May 29, 1966 |work=The New York Times |language=en-US |issn=0362-4331|url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1966/05/29/140000432.pdf }}</ref> The World Trade Center was one of the most-striking American implementations of the architectural ethic of [[Le Corbusier]] and was the seminal expression of Yamasaki's gothic modernist tendencies.{{sfnp|Darton|1999|pp=32\u201334}} He was also inspired by [[Arabic architecture]], elements of which he incorporated in the building's design, having previously designed Saudi Arabia's [[Dhahran International Airport]] with the [[Saudi Binladin Group]].<ref name=\"Grudin2010\">{{cite book |first=Robert |last=Grudin |title=Design And Truth |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=KHFoCxkdiUIC&pg=PA39 |date=April 20, 2010 |publisher=[[Yale University Press]] |isbn=978-0-300-16203-5 |pages=39|access-date=April 18, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160527162624/https://books.google.com/books?id=KHFoCxkdiUIC&pg=PA39|archive-date=May 27, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"Kerr 2001\">{{cite web |last=Kerr |first=Laurie |title=Bin Laden's special complaint with the World Trade Center. |website=[[Slate (magazine)|Slate Magazine]] |date=December 28, 2001 |url=http://www.slate.com/articles/arts/culturebox/2001/12/the_mosque_to_commerce.html |accessdate=October 12, 2015 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150919030203/http://www.slate.com/articles/arts/culturebox/2001/12/the_mosque_to_commerce.html | archive-date=September 19, 2015 | url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n[[File:World Trade Center Building Design with Floor and Elevator Arrangment m.svg|thumb|left|A typical floor layout and elevator arrangement of the WTC towers]]\nA major limiting factor in building height is the issue of elevators; the taller the building, the more elevators are needed to service it, requiring more space-consuming elevator banks.{{sfnp|Goldberger|2004|p=25}} Yamasaki and the engineers decided to use a new system with two \"[[sky lobby|sky lobbies]]\"\u2014floors where people could switch from a large-capacity express elevator to a local elevator that goes to each floor in a section. This system, inspired by the local-express train operation used in New York City's subway system,{{sfnp|Gillespie|1999|p=75}} allowed the design to stack local elevators within the same elevator shaft. Located on the 44th and 78th floors of each tower, the sky lobbies enabled the elevators to be used efficiently. This increased the amount of usable space on each floor from 62 to 75 percent by reducing the number of elevator shafts.{{sfnp|Gillespie|1999|pp=75\u201378}} Altogether, the World Trade Center had 95 express and local elevators.<ref name=\"ruchelman-p11\">{{Cite book |last=Ruchelman |first=Leonard I. |title=The World Trade Center: Politics and Policies of Skyscraper Development |publisher=[[Syracuse University Press]] |year=1977 |isbn=978-0-81562-180-5 |page=11}}</ref>\n\nThe structural engineering firm Worthington, Skilling, Helle & Jackson worked to implement Yamasaki's design, developing the [[tube (structure)|framed-tube structural system]] used in the twin towers.{{sfnp|NIST NCSTAR 1|2005|page=6 <!--|quote=Skilling and his team rose to the challenge of providing the required load capacity within Yamasaki's design concept. They incorporated an innovative framed-tube concept for the structural system.-->}} The Port Authority's Engineering Department served as [[geotechnical engineering|foundation engineers]], Joseph R. Loring & Associates as [[electrical engineering|electrical engineers]], and [[Jaros, Baum & Bolles|Jaros, Baum & Bolles (JB&B)]] as [[mechanical engineering|mechanical engineers]]. [[Tishman Realty & Construction|Tishman Realty & Construction Company]] was the [[general contractor]] on the World Trade Center project. [[Guy F. Tozzoli]], director of the World Trade Department at the Port Authority, and Rino M. Monti, the Port Authority's Chief Engineer, oversaw the project.{{sfnp|NIST NCSTAR 1-1|2005|p=1}} As an interstate agency, the Port Authority was not subject to the local laws and regulations of the City of New York, including [[building code]]s. Nonetheless, the World Trade Center's structural engineers ended up following draft versions of New York City's new 1968 building codes.{{sfnp|NIST NCSTAR 1-1|2005|pp=40\u201342}}\n[[File:WTC-Perspektive.jpg|thumb|upright|The exterior structure of the Twin Towers]]\nThe framed-tube design, introduced in the 1960s by [[Bangladeshi-American]] structural engineer [[Fazlur Rahman Khan]],<ref>{{cite web|author=Alfred Swenson & Pao-Chi Chang|title=Building construction: High-rise construction since 1945|publisher=[[Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica]]|year=2008|url=https://www.britannica.com/technology/building-construction/High-rise-construction-since-1945|accessdate=2019-08-20|quote= The framed tube, which Khan developed for concrete structures, was applied to other tall steel buildings. }}</ref> was a new approach that allowed more open floor plans than the traditional design that distributed columns throughout the interior to support building loads. Each of the World Trade Center towers had 236 high-strength, load-bearing perimeter steel columns which acted as [[Vierendeel truss]]es.{{sfnp|World Trade Center Building Performance Study|2002|page=2.33|quote=... the loads initially carried by the damaged exterior columns were transferred by Vierendeel truss action to the remaining exterior columns immediately adjacent to the impact area.}}{{sfnp|NIST NCSTAR 1|2005|page=6}} The perimeter columns were spaced closely together to form a strong, rigid wall structure, supporting virtually all lateral loads such as wind loads, and sharing the gravity load with the core columns.{{sfnp|NIST NCSTAR 1|2005|page=6}} The perimeter structure containing 59 columns per side was constructed with extensive use of prefabricated modular pieces, each consisting of three columns, three stories tall, connected by [[wikt:spandrel|spandrel]] plates.{{sfnp|NIST NCSTAR 1-1|2005|p=10}} The spandrel plates were welded to the columns to create the modular pieces off-site at the fabrication shop.{{sfnp|NIST NCSTAR 1-1|2005|p=8}} Adjacent modules were bolted together with the splices occurring at mid-span of the columns and spandrels. The spandrel plates were located at each floor, transmitting [[shear stress]] between columns, allowing them to work together in resisting lateral loads. The joints between modules were staggered vertically, so that the column splices between adjacent modules were not at the same floor.{{sfnp|NIST NCSTAR 1-1|2005|pp=40\u201342}} Below 7th floor to the foundation, there were fewer, wider-spaced perimeter columns to accommodate doorways.{{sfnp|NIST NCSTAR 1-1|2005|page=10}}{{sfnp|NIST NCSTAR 1|2005|page=6}}<!-- Deleted image removed: [[File:WTC Twin Towers NASA picture.jpg|thumb|View of the Towers from the corner of building 5, February 1997]] -->\n\nThe core of the towers housed the elevator and utility shafts, restrooms, three stairwells, and other support spaces. The core of each tower was a rectangular area {{convert|87|by|135|ft|m}} and contained 47 steel columns running from the bedrock to the top of the tower. The large, column-free space between the perimeter and core was bridged by prefabricated floor trusses. The floors supported their own weight as well as [[live loads]], providing lateral stability to the exterior walls and distributing wind loads among the exterior walls.{{sfnp|NIST NCSTAR 1-1|2005|pp=8\u20139}} The floors consisted of {{convert|4|in|cm|adj=on}} thick  lightweight concrete slabs laid on a fluted steel deck. A grid of lightweight bridging trusses and main trusses supported the floors.{{sfnp|NIST NCSTAR 1-1|2005|p=10}} The trusses connected to the perimeter at alternate columns and were on 6&nbsp;foot 8&nbsp;inch (2.03&nbsp;m) centers. The top chords of the trusses were bolted to seats welded to the spandrels on the exterior side and a channel welded to the core columns on the interior side. The floors were connected to the perimeter spandrel plates with [[viscoelasticity|viscoelastic]] dampers that helped reduce the amount of sway felt by building occupants.\n\nHat [[truss]]es (or \"outrigger trusses\") located from the 107th floor to the top of the buildings were designed to support a tall communication antenna on top of each building.{{sfnp|NIST NCSTAR 1-1|2005|p=10}} Only 1&nbsp;WTC (north tower) actually had an antenna fitted; it was added in 1978.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.pbs.org/wgbh/amex/newyork/sfeature/sf_building_pop_01_qt.html |title=New York: A Documentary Film \u2013 The Center of the World (Construction Footage) |publisher=Port Authority / PBS |accessdate=May 16, 2007 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070316163530/http://www.pbs.org/wgbh/amex/newyork/sfeature/sf_building_pop_01_qt.html |archive-date=March 16, 2007 |url-status=live}}</ref> The truss system consisted of six trusses along the long axis of the core and four along the short axis. This truss system allowed some load redistribution between the perimeter and core columns and supported the transmission tower.{{sfnp|NIST NCSTAR 1-1|2005|p=10}}\n\nThe framed-tube design, using steel core and perimeter columns protected with sprayed-on fire resistant material, created a relatively lightweight structure that would sway more in response to the wind compared to traditional structures, such as the [[Empire State Building]] that have thick, heavy masonry for [[fireproofing]] of steel structural elements.{{sfnp|Glanz|Lipton|2003|p=138}} During the design process, [[wind tunnel]] tests were done to establish design wind pressures that the World Trade Center towers could be subjected to and structural response to those forces.{{sfnp|NIST NCSTAR 1-1|2005|p=65}} Experiments also were done to evaluate how much sway occupants could comfortably tolerate; however, many subjects experienced dizziness and other ill effects.{{sfnp|Glanz|Lipton|2003|pp=139\u2013144}} One of the chief engineers [[Leslie Robertson]] worked with Canadian engineer [[Alan Garnett Davenport|Alan G. Davenport]] to develop viscoelastic [[damping|dampers]] to absorb some of the sway. These viscoelastic dampers, used throughout the structures at the joints between floor trusses and perimeter columns along with some other structural modifications, reduced the building sway to an acceptable level.{{sfnp|Glanz|Lipton|2003|pp=160\u2013167}}\n\n===Construction===\n[[File:WTC-1971-under-construction.jpg|thumb|left|upright|World Trade Center under construction in May 1971]]\n\nIn March 1965, the Port Authority began acquiring property at the World Trade Center site.<ref name=\"nyt 19650329\">{{Cite news |title=Port Agency Buys Downtown Tract |last=Ingraham |first=Joseph C. |date=March 29, 1965 |work=The New York Times |language=en-US |issn=0362-4331 |url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1965/03/29/96702632.pdf }}</ref> Demolition work began on {{Nowrap|March 21}}, 1966, to clear thirteen square blocks of low rise buildings in Radio Row for its construction.{{sfnp|Gillespie|1999|p=61}} Groundbreaking for the construction of the World Trade Center took place on {{Nowrap|August 5}}, 1966.{{sfnp|World Trade Center Building Performance Study|2002|page=1.2}}\n\nThe site of the World Trade Center was located on landfill with the [[bedrock]] located {{convert|65|ft|m}} below.<ref name=\"iglauer\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.newyorker.com/archive/1972/11/04/1972_11_04_130_TNY_CARDS_000308769 |title=The Biggest Foundation |last=Iglauer |first=Edith |date=November 4, 1972 |work=[[The New Yorker]] |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20011218095545/http://www.newyorker.com/FROM_THE_ARCHIVE/ARCHIVES/?010917fr_archive06 |archivedate=December 18, 2001}}</ref> To construct the World Trade Center, it was necessary to build a \"[[the Bathtub|bathtub]]\" with a [[slurry wall]] around the [[West Street]] side of the site, to keep water from the Hudson River out.<ref>{{Cite news |title=Tall Towers will Sit on Deep Foundations |last=Kapp |first=Martin S |publisher=[[Engineering News-Record]] |date=July 9, 1964}}</ref> The slurry method selected by the Port Authority's chief engineer, John M. Kyle, Jr., involved digging a trench, and as excavation proceeded, filling the space with a \"slurry\" mixture composed of [[bentonite]] and water, which plugged holes and kept groundwater out. When the trench was dug out, a steel cage was inserted and concrete was poured in, forcing the \"slurry\" out. It took fourteen months for the slurry wall to be completed. It was necessary before excavation of material from the interior of the site could begin.{{sfnp|Gillespie|1999|p=68}} The {{convert|1200000|yd3|m3}} of excavated material were used (along with other fill and dredge material) to expand the Manhattan shoreline across West Street to form [[Battery Park City]].{{sfnp|Gillespie|1999|p=71}}<ref>{{Cite news |title=New York Gets $90&nbsp;Million Worth of Land for Nothing |publisher=Engineering News- Record |date=April 18, 1968}}</ref>\n\nIn January 1967, the Port Authority awarded $74&nbsp;million in contracts to various steel suppliers.<ref name=\"nyt-1967jan24\">{{Cite news |url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1967/01/24/82570486.pdf |title=Contracts Totaling $74,079,000 Awarded for the Trade Center |work=The New York Times |language=en-US |issn=0362-4331 |date=January 24, 1967}}</ref> Construction work began on the North Tower in {{Nowrap|August 1968}}, and construction on the South Tower was under way by {{Nowrap|January 1969}}.<ref name=\"pbstimeline\">{{cite web |url=https://www.pbs.org/wgbh/amex/newyork/timeline/index.html |title=Timeline: World Trade Center chronology |publisher=PBS \u2013 [[American Experience]] |accessdate=May 15, 2007 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070502225357/http://www.pbs.org/wgbh/amex/newyork/timeline/index.html |archive-date=May 2, 2007 |url-status=live}}</ref> The original [[Downtown Hudson Tubes|Hudson Tubes]], which carried PATH trains into Hudson Terminal, remained in service during the construction process until 1971, when a [[World Trade Center (PATH station)|new station]] opened.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Carroll |first=Maurice |url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1968/12/30/77185607.pdf |title=A Section of the Hudson Tubes is Turned into Elevated Tunnel |date=December 30, 1968 |work=The New York Times |language=en-US |issn=0362-4331}}</ref> The [[topping out]] ceremony of 1&nbsp;WTC (North Tower) took place on {{Nowrap|December 23}}, 1970, while 2&nbsp;WTC's ceremony (South Tower) occurred on {{Nowrap|July 19}}, 1971.<ref name=\"pbstimeline\" /> Extensive use of prefabricated components helped to speed up the construction process, and the first tenants moved into the North Tower in {{Nowrap|December 15, 1970}}, while it was still under construction,<ref>{{cite book |title=Design, Construction, and Maintenance of Structural and Life Safety Systems (NCSTAR 1-1) |publisher=National Institute of Standards and Technology |last=Lew |first=H. S. |first2=Richard W. |last2=Bukowski |first3=Nicholas J. |last3=Carino |date=September 2005 |page=xxxvi}}</ref><ref name=\"PANYNJ\">{{cite web |title=History of the Twin Towers |url=http://www.panynj.gov/wtcprogress/history-twin-towers.html |publisher=[[Port Authority of New York and New Jersey]] |date=June 1, 2014 |accessdate=August 17, 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131228040848/http://www.panynj.gov/wtcprogress/history-twin-towers.html |archivedate=December 28, 2013 }}</ref> while the South Tower began accepting tenants in {{Nowrap|January 1972}}.{{sfnp|NIST NCSTAR 1-1|2005|p=xxxvi}} When the World Trade Center twin towers were completed, the total costs to the Port Authority had reached $900&nbsp;million.{{sfnp|Cudahy|2002|p=58}} The ribbon cutting ceremony took place on {{Nowrap|April 4}}, 1973.{{sfnp|Gillespie|1999|p=134}}\n\nIn addition to the twin towers, the plan for the World Trade Center complex included four other low-rise buildings, which were built in the early 1970s. The 47-story 7&nbsp;World Trade Center building was added in the 1980s, to the north of the main complex. Altogether, the main World Trade Center complex occupied a {{convert|16|acre|m2|adj=on}} [[City block#Superblock|superblock]].<ref name=\"Nobel 2005 54\">{{cite book |last=Nobel |first=Philip |title=Sixteen acres : architecture and the outrageous struggle for the future of Ground Zero |publisher=[[Metropolitan Books]], Henry Holt and Co |location=New York |year=2005 |isbn=978-0-8050-7494-9 |page=[https://archive.org/details/sixteenacresoutr00nobe/page/54 54] |url=https://archive.org/details/sixteenacresoutr00nobe/page/54 }}</ref><ref name=Mumford1974/>\n\n===Criticism===\n[[File:WTC Building Arrangement and Site Plan.svg|thumb|The WTC site building arrangement]]\n\nPlans to build the World Trade Center were controversial. Its site was the location of Radio Row, home to hundreds of commercial and industrial tenants, property owners, small businesses, and approximately 100 residents, many of whom fiercely resisted forced relocation.{{sfnp|Gillespie|1999|pp=42\u201344}} A group of affected small businesses sought an [[injunction]] challenging the Port Authority's power of eminent domain.<ref>{{Cite news |title=Injunction Asked on Trade Center |date=June 27, 1962 |work=The New York Times |language=en-US |issn=0362-4331 |last=Clark |first=Alfred E.|url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1962/06/27/82049659.pdf }}</ref> The case made its way through the court system to the [[Supreme Court of the United States|United States Supreme Court]]; it refused to hear the case.<ref name=\"nyt-1963nov13\">{{Cite news |url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1963/11/13/89971855.pdf |title=High Court Plea is Lost by Foes of Trade Center |last=Arnold |first=Martin |work=The New York Times |language=en-US |issn=0362-4331 |date=November 13, 1963}}</ref>\n\nPrivate real estate developers and members of the Real Estate Board of New York, led by Empire State Building owner [[Lawrence A. Wien]], expressed concerns about this much \"subsidized\" office space going on the open market, competing with the private sector, when there was already a glut of vacancies.{{sfnp|Gillespie|1999|pp=49\u201350}}<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1964/02/14/new-fight-begun-on-trade-center.html |title=New Fight Begun on Trade Center |last=Knowles |first=Clayton |date=February 14, 1964 |work=The New York Times |language=en-US |issn=0362-4331}}</ref> The World Trade Center itself was not rented out completely until after 1979 and then only because the complex's subsidy by the Port Authority made rents charged for its office space cheaper than those for comparable space in other buildings.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.theatlanticcities.com/jobs-and-economy/2012/09/original-world-trade-centers-rocky-real-estate-history/3240/ |title=The World Trade Center's Rocky Real Estate History |first=Eric |last=Jaffe |date=September 12, 2012 |work=The Atlantic Cities |publisher=[[Atlantic Media Company]] |accessdate=September 11, 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120915000117/http://www.theatlanticcities.com/jobs-and-economy/2012/09/original-world-trade-centers-rocky-real-estate-history/3240/ |archive-date=September 15, 2012 |url-status=live}}</ref> Others questioned whether the Port Authority should have taken on a project described by some as a \"mistaken social priority\".<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1969/11/12/79436401.pdf |title=Kheel Urges Port Authority to Sell Trade Center |date=November 12, 1969 |work=The New York Times |language=en-US |issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\nThe World Trade Center's design [[aesthetics]] attracted criticism from the [[American Institute of Architects]] and other groups.<ref name=\"nyt-1966may29\" /><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1964/03/12/archives/letters-to-the-times-marring-citys-skyline-trade-center-buildings.html?searchResultPosition=1 |title=Marring City's Skyline |last=Steese |first=Edward |date=March 10, 1964 |work=The New York Times |language=en-US |issn=0362-4331}}</ref> [[Lewis Mumford]], author of ''[[The City in History]]'' and other works on [[urban planning]], criticized the project, describing it and other new skyscrapers as \"just glass-and-metal filing cabinets\".<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1967/03/22/90299847.pdf |title=Mumford Finds City Strangled By Excess of Cars and People |last=Whitman |first=Alden |work=The New York Times |language=en-US |issn=0362-4331 |date=March 22, 1967}}</ref> The Twin Towers were described as looking similar to \"the boxes that the Empire State Building and the [[Chrysler Building]] came in\".<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1985/02/27/nyregion/about-new-york-39-years-of-observing-the-observers.html |title=About New York: 39 years observing the observers |last1=Geist |first1=William |date=February 27, 1985 |work=The New York Times |language=en-US |issn=0362-4331 |access-date=May 19, 2019}}</ref> Many disliked the twin towers' narrow office windows, which were only {{convert|18|in|cm}} wide and framed by pillars that restricted views on each side to narrow slots.<ref name=\"pekala\" /> Activist and sociologist [[Jane Jacobs]] argued the waterfront should be kept open for New Yorkers to enjoy.<ref>{{cite book |last=Alexiou |first=Alice |title=Jane Jacobs: Urban Visionary |publisher=[[Rutgers University Press]] | location=New Brunswick, N.J |year=2006 |isbn=978-0-8135-3792-4 |page=78}}</ref>\n\nSome critics regarded the trade center's \"superblock\", [[#On the surrounding community|replacing a more traditional, dense neighborhood]], as an inhospitable environment that disrupted the complicated traffic network typical of Manhattan. For example, in his book ''[[The Pentagon of Power]]'', Lewis Mumford denounced the center as an \"example of the purposeless giantism and technological exhibitionism that are now eviscerating the living tissue of every great city\".<ref name=Mumford1974>{{cite book |last=Mumford |first=Lewis |title=The Pentagon of Power |publisher=[[Harcourt, Brace, Jovanovich]] | location=New York |series=[[The Myth of the Machine]] |volume=II |year=1974 |isbn=978-0-15-671610-9 |page=}}</ref>\n\n==Complex==\nThe World Trade Center complex housed more than 430 companies that were engaged in various commercial activities.<ref name=\"edcnn\">{{cite web|url=http://edition.cnn.com/SPECIALS/2001/trade.center/tenants1.html|title=List of World Trade Center tenants|website=cnn.com|publisher=CNN|access-date=5 September 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171002025826/http://edition.cnn.com/SPECIALS/2001/trade.center/tenants1.html|archive-date=2017-10-02|url-status=live}}</ref> On a typical weekday, an estimated 50,000 people worked in the complex and another 140,000 passed through as visitors.<ref name=edcnn/> The complex hosted {{convert|13,400,000|ft2|m2}} of office space,<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9F01E4D81030F935A35752C0A9649C8B63 |title=Commercial Property; In Office Market, a Time of Uncertainty |work=The New York Times |language=en-US |issn=0362-4331 |last=Holusha |first=John |date=January 6, 2002 |accessdate=November 21, 2008}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_m3601/is_30_48/ai_83762552 |archive-url=https://archive.is/20120526191512/http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_m3601/is_30_48/ai_83762552 |url-status=dead |archive-date=May 26, 2012 |title=Ford recounts details of Sept. 11 |work=[[Real Estate Weekly]] |date=February 27, 2002 |publisher=BNET |accessdate=January 3, 2009}}</ref> and was so large that it had its own zip code: [[10048 (ZIP code)|10048]].<ref>{{Cite news |title='Not Deliverable';Mail still says 'One World Trade Center' |publisher=[[Newsday (New York)]] |date=February 4, 2003 |last=Olshan |first=Jeremy}}</ref> The towers offered expansive views from the observation deck atop the South Tower and the [[Windows on the World]] restaurant on top of the North Tower. The Twin Towers became known worldwide, appearing in numerous movies and television shows as well as on postcards and other merchandise. It became a New York icon, in the same league as the Empire State Building, the Chrysler Building, and the [[Statue of Liberty]].{{sfnp|Gillespie|1999|p=5}} The World Trade Center was compared to [[Rockefeller Center]], which David Rockefeller's brother Nelson had developed in midtown Manhattan.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.pbs.org/wgbh/nova/tech/twin-towers-of-innovation.html |title=Twin Towers of Innovation \u2014 NOVA {{!}} PBS|last=Tyson|first=Peter|date=April 30, 2002|website=www.pbs.org|access-date=February 22, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180223110826/http://www.pbs.org/wgbh/nova/tech/twin-towers-of-innovation.html|archive-date=February 23, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===North and South Towers===\n[[File:World Trade Center lobby, 08-19-2000.png|thumb|Lobby of the North Tower, looking south along the east side of the building, August 19, 2000]]\nOne World Trade Center and Two World Trade Center, commonly referred to as the Twin Towers, were designed by architect Minoru Yamasaki as framed tube structures, which provided tenants with open floor plans, uninterrupted by columns or walls.{{sfnp|ps=.|NIST NCSTAR 1|2005|pages=5\u20136}}<ref>{{cite journal |last=Taylor |first=R. E. |date=December 1966 |title=Computers and the Design of the World Trade Center |journal=Journal of the Structural Division |volume=92 |issue=ST\u20136 |pages=75\u201391}}</ref> They were the main buildings of the World Trade Center.<ref name=\"pbstimeline\" /> Construction of the North Tower at One World Trade Center began in 1966 with the South Tower at Two World Trade Center.<ref name=\"WSO\">{{cite web |url=http://w.skyscraper.org/TALLEST_TOWERS/t_wtc.htm |title=The World Trade Center: Statistics and History |access-date=August 13, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150916031526/http://w.skyscraper.org/TALLEST_TOWERS/t_wtc.htm|archive-date=September 16, 2015|url-status=live }}</ref> When completed in 1972, 1&nbsp;World Trade Center became the tallest building in the world for two years, surpassing the Empire State Building after its 40-year reign. The North Tower stood {{convert|1368|ft|m}} tall<ref name=WSO/> and featured a {{convert|362|foot|m}} telecommunications antenna or mast that was built on the roof in 1978. With this addition, the highest point of the North Tower reached {{convert|1730|ft|m}}.<ref name=\"mcdowell\" /> Chicago's [[Sears Tower]], finished in {{Nowrap|May 1973}}, reached {{convert|1450|ft}} at the rooftop.<ref>{{cite web |title=Willis Tower Building Information |url=http://www.willistower.com/propertyprofile.html |accessdate=December 1, 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090719075320/http://www.willistower.com/propertyprofile.html |archivedate=July 19, 2009 }}</ref>\n\n[[File:World Trade Center South Tower lobby interior, 1988.jpg|thumbnail|left|South Tower lobby interior, overlooking the elevator core and red carpet from the balcony, October 1988]]\n\nWhen completed in 1973, the South Tower became the second tallest building in the world at {{Convert|1362|ft|m}}. Its rooftop observation deck was {{convert|1362|ft|m|abbr=on}} high and its indoor observation deck was {{convert|1310|ft|m|abbr=on}} high.<ref name=\"mcdowell\"/> Each tower stood over {{convert|1350|ft|m}} high, and occupied about {{convert|1|acre|m2}} of the total {{convert|16|acre|m2}} of the site's land. During a press conference in 1973, Yamasaki was asked, \"Why two 110-story buildings? Why not one 220-story building?\" His [[tongue-in-cheek]] response was: \"I didn't want to lose the human scale.\"<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.enr.com/new/A0816.asp |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20020611065443/http://www.enr.com/new/A0816.asp |archivedate=June 11, 2002 |title=1973: World Trade Center Is Dynamic Duo of Height |publisher=Engineering News-Record |date=August 16, 1999}}</ref>\n\nThroughout their existence, the twin towers had [[List of buildings with 100 floors or more|more floors]] (at 110) than any other building.<ref name=\"mcdowell\"/> Their floor counts were not matched until the construction of the [[Willis Tower|Sears Tower]], and they were not surpassed until the construction of the [[Burj Khalifa]], which opened in 2010.<ref name=\"burjdubai\">{{cite news |url=http://gulfnews.com/business/property/uae/official-opening-of-iconic-burj-dubai-announced-1.523471 |title=Official Opening of Iconic Burj Dubai Announced |publisher=[[Gulf News]] |date=November 4, 2009 |accessdate=November 4, 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091106052129/http://gulfnews.com/business/property/uae/official-opening-of-iconic-burj-dubai-announced-1.523471 |archivedate=November 6, 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/business/8439618.stm |title=World's tallest building opens in Dubai |date=January 4, 2010 |publisher=[[BBC News]] |accessdate=January 4, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100105054239/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/business/8439618.stm |archive-date=January 5, 2010 |url-status=live}}</ref> Each tower had a total mass of around 500,000 tons.<ref>{{cite journal |last=Eagar |first=Thomas W. |last2=Musso |first2=Christopher |title=Why did the world trade center collapse? Science, engineering, and speculation |journal=JOM |publisher=[[Springer Nature]] |volume=53 |issue=12 |year=2001 |issn=1047-4838 |doi=10.1007/s11837-001-0003-1 |pages=8\u201311|bibcode=2001JOM....53l...8E }}</ref>\n\n===Austin J. Tobin Plaza===\n[[File:Austin_Tobin_Plaza_Marriott_World_Trade_Center_-_1995.jpg|thumb|The five-acre Austin J. Tobin Plaza, looking west toward the Marriott Hotel which was in 3 World Trade Center]]\n\nThe original World Trade Center had a massive, five-acre plaza which all other buildings, including the Twin Towers centered around. In 1982, the immense plaza between the twin towers was renamed after the man who authorized the construction of the original World Trade Center. Port Authority's late chairman, [[Austin J. Tobin]].{{sfnp|Gillespie|1999|p=123}} During the summer, the Port Authority installed a portable stage, typically backed up against the North Tower within Tobin Plaza for performers.{{sfnp|Gillespie|1999|p=214}} The odd layout for performances was due to the installation of a [[The Sphere|sculpture]] in the center of the plaza, which only allowed for about 6,000 fans. <ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.goodreads.com/author/show/6572997.Lonnie_Ostrow/blog |title=Lonnie Ostrow's Blog |publisher=Ostrow, Lonnie|url-status=live}}</ref> For many years, the Plaza was often beset by brisk winds at ground level owing to the [[Venturi effect]] between the two towers.<ref>{{Cite news |title=At New Trade Center, Seeking Lively (but Secure) Streets |work=The New York Times |language=en-US |issn=0362-4331 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2006/12/07/nyregion/07blocks.html?fta=y |date=December 7, 2006 |last=Dunlap |first=David W. |access-date=February 23, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160415180330/http://www.nytimes.com/2006/12/07/nyregion/07blocks.html?fta=y |archive-date=April 15, 2016 |url-status=live}}</ref> Some gusts were so strong that pedestrians' travel had to be aided by ropes.<ref>{{Cite news |title=Girding Against Return of the Windy City in Manhattan |work=The New York Times |language=en-US |issn=0362-4331 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2004/03/25/nyregion/25blocks.html |date=March 25, 2004 |last=Dunlap |first=David W. |access-date=February 23, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150828144027/http://www.nytimes.com/2004/03/25/nyregion/25blocks.html |archive-date=August 28, 2015 |url-status=live}}</ref> In 1999, the outdoor plaza reopened after undergoing $12&nbsp;million in renovations. This involved replacing [[marble]] pavers with gray and pink [[granite]] stones, adding new benches, planters, new restaurants, food kiosks and outdoor dining areas.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.panynj.gov/pr/71-99.html |title=World Trade Center Plaza Reopens with Summer-long Performing Arts Festival |publisher=[[Port Authority of New York and New Jersey]] |date=June 9, 1999 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081228084900/http://www.panynj.gov/pr/71-99.html |archivedate=December 28, 2008}}</ref>\n\n===Top of the World observation deck===\n[[File:Two World Trade Center Observation Deck.jpg|thumb|Visitors on the viewing platform on the South Tower's roof, looking north toward [[Midtown Manhattan]] in 1984]]\n\nAlthough most of the space in the World Trade Center complex was off-limits to the public, the South Tower featured a public observation deck on the 107th floor called Top of the World.{{sfn|NIST NCSTAR 1-1|2005|page=158 <!--Similar to the Windows on the World facilities on the 106th and 107th floors of WTC 1, there was a public observation deck on the 107th floor of WTC 2 called Top of the World-->}}{{sfn|NIST NCSTAR 1|2005|page=58}} After paying an entrance fee, visitors were required to pass through security checks added after the [[1993 World Trade Center bombing]].<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9804E1DE1E3EF937A15751C0A961958260 |title=Metal Detectors, Common at Other City Landmarks, Are Not Used |last=Onishi |first=Norimitsu |date=February 24, 1997 |work=The New York Times |language=en-US |issn=0362-4331 |accessdate=November 21, 2008}}</ref> They were then sent to the 107th-floor indoor observatory at a height of {{convert|1310|ft|m}} by a dedicated express elevator.{{sfn|NIST NCSTAR 1-1|2005|page=158}} The exterior columns were narrowed to allow 28&nbsp;inches of window width between them. The Port Authority renovated the observatory in 1995, then leased it to Ogden Entertainment to operate. Attractions added to the observation deck included a theater showing a film of a helicopter tour around the city.{{sfn|NIST NCSTAR 1-1|2005|page=158}} The 107th-floor food court was designed with a subway car theme and featured [[Sbarro]] and [[Nathan's Famous]] Hot Dogs.<ref name=\"mcdowell\">{{Cite news |url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9802EED7133CF932A25757C0A961958260 |title=At Trade Center Deck, Views Are Lofty, as Are the Prices |last=McDowell |first=Edwin |date=April 11, 1997 |work=The New York Times |language=en-US |issn=0362-4331 |accessdate=November 21, 2008 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080410152849/http://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9802EED7133CF932A25757C0A961958260 |archive-date=April 10, 2008 |url-status=live}}</ref>{{sfnp|Darton|1999|p=152}} Weather permitting, visitors could ride two short escalators up from the 107th-floor viewing area to an outdoor platform at a height of {{convert|1377|ft|m|abbr=on}}.{{sfn|NIST NCSTAR 1-1|2005|page=158}}<ref>{{cite book |last=Adams |first=Arthur |title=The Hudson River Guidebook |url=https://archive.org/details/hudsonriverguide0000adam |url-access=registration |publisher=[[Fordham University Press]] | location=New York |year=1996 |isbn=978-0-8232-1680-2 |page=[https://archive.org/details/hudsonriverguide0000adam/page/87 87]}}</ref> On a clear day, visitors could see up to {{convert|50|mi|km}}.<ref name=\"mcdowell\" /> An anti-suicide fence was placed on the roof itself, with the viewing platform set back and elevated above it, requiring only an ordinary railing. This left the view unobstructed, unlike the observation deck of the Empire State Building.{{sfnp|Darton|1999|p=152}}\n\n===Windows on the World restaurant===\n{{Main|Windows on the World}}\n\n[[File:Windows on the world restaurant interior, 1999.jpg|thumb|Windows on the World restaurant interior, November 4, 1999]]\n\nWindows on the World, the restaurant on the North Tower's 106th and 107th floors, opened in {{Nowrap|April 1976}}. It was developed by  restaurateur [[Joe Baum]] at a cost of more than $17&nbsp;million.<ref name=\"zraly\">{{cite book |last=Zraly |first=Kevin |title=Windows on the world complete wine course |publisher=[[Sterling Epicure]] | location=New York |year=2006 |isbn=978-1-4549-2106-6 |page=260}}</ref> As well as the main restaurant, two offshoots were located at the top of the North Tower: Hors d'Oeuvrerie (offered a [[Cuisine of Denmark#Det kolde bord|Danish smorgasbord]] during the day and sushi in the evening) and Cellar in the Sky (a small wine bar).<ref name=\"grimes\">{{Cite news |url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9C06E0D9153BF93AA2575AC0A9679C8B63&sec=travel&spon=&pagewanted=all |title=Windows That Rose So Close To the Sun |date=September 19, 2001 |work=The New York Times |language=en-US |issn=0362-4331 |last=Grimes |first=William |access-date=September 18, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081017071647/http://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9C06E0D9153BF93AA2575AC0A9679C8B63&sec=travel&spon=&pagewanted=all |archive-date=October 17, 2008 |url-status=live}}</ref> Windows on the World also had a wine school program run by [[Kevin Zraly]], who published a book on the course.<ref>{{Cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=pkXDYgEACAAJ |title=Kevin Zraly's Complete Wine Course |last=Zraly |first=Kevin |date=2011 |publisher=Sterling Publishing Company, Incorporated |isbn=978-1-4027-8793-5 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nWindows on the World was closed following the 1993 World Trade Center bombing.<ref name=\"zraly\" /> When it reopened in 1996, the Greatest Bar on Earth and Wild Blue replaced the original restaurant offshoots.<ref name=\"grimes\" /> In 2000, its last full year of operation, Windows on the World reported revenues of $37&nbsp;million, making it the highest-grossing restaurant in the United States.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9D07E2DA103AF937A35755C0A9649C8B63 |title=Windows on the World Workers Say Their Boss Didn't Do Enough |last=Greenhouse |first=Steven |date=June 4, 2002 |work=The New York Times |language=en-US |issn=0362-4331}}</ref> The Sky Dive Restaurant, on the 44th floor of the North Tower, was also operated by Windows on the World.<ref name=\"grimes\" />\n\nIn its last iteration, Windows on the World received mixed reviews. [[Ruth Reichl]], a ''New York Times'' food critic, said in December 1996 that \"nobody will ever go to Windows on the World just to eat, but even the fussiest food person can now be content dining at one of New York's favorite tourist destinations\". She gave the restaurant two out of four stars, signifying a \"very good\" quality.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1997/12/31/dining/restaurants-food-that-s-nearly-worthy-of-the-view.html |title=Restaurants; Food That's Nearly Worthy of the View |last=Reichl |first=Ruth |date=December 31, 1997 |work=The New York Times |language=en-US |issn=0362-4331|access-date=February 22, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180222165429/http://www.nytimes.com/1997/12/31/dining/restaurants-food-that-s-nearly-worthy-of-the-view.html|archive-date=February 22, 2018|url-status=live }}</ref> In his 2009 book ''Appetite'', William Grimes wrote that, \"At Windows, New York was the main course\".<ref>{{Cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=w9pLESNSYb8C&pg=PA281 |title=Appetite City: A Culinary History of New York |last=Grimes |first=William |date=October 13, 2009 |publisher=Farrar, Straus and Giroux |isbn=978-1-42999-027-1 |pages=281 |language=en}}</ref> In 2014, Ryan Sutton of ''[[Eater.com]]'' compared the now-destroyed restaurant's cuisine to that of its replacement, [[One World Observatory]]. He said, \"Windows helped usher in a new era of captive audience dining in that the restaurant was a destination in itself, rather than a lazy by-product of the vital institution it resided in.\"<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://ny.eater.com/2015/6/30/8862293/one-world-trade-dining |title=Everything You Need to Know About Dining at One World Trade |last=Sutton |first=Ryan |date=June 30, 2015 |work=Eater NY|access-date=February 22, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180223050650/https://ny.eater.com/2015/6/30/8862293/one-world-trade-dining|archive-date=February 23, 2018|url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n===Other buildings===\n\n[[File:Twin Towers-NYC.jpg|thumb|The [[Brookfield Place (New York City)|World Financial Center]] and [[Battery Park City]], next to the World Trade Center, were built on [[Land reclamation|reclaimed land]].]]\nFive smaller buildings stood on the {{convert|16|acre|m2|adj=on}} block.{{sfnp|Gillespie|1999|p=226}} One was the 22-floor hotel, which opened at the southwest corner of the site in 1981 as the Vista Hotel;<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1981/04/02/nyregion/hotel-in-the-trade-center-greets-its-first-100-guests.html |title=Hotel In The Trade Center Greets Its First 100 Guests |date=April 2, 1981 |accessdate=May 23, 2018 |newspaper=The New York Times |language=en-US |issn=0362-4331 }}</ref> in 1995, it became the [[Marriott World Trade Center]] (3&nbsp;WTC).{{sfnp|Gillespie|1999|p=226}} Three low-rise buildings (4&nbsp;WTC, 5&nbsp;WTC, and 6&nbsp;WTC), which were steel-framed office buildings, also stood around the plaza.{{sfn|World Trade Center Building Performance Study|2002|page=4.1}} [[6&nbsp;World Trade Center]], at the northwest corner, housed the [[U.S. Customs and Border Protection|United States Customs Service]].<ref name=Landesman>{{cite book |last1=Landesman |first1=Linda Y |first2=Isaac B. |last2=Weisfuse |title=Case Studies in Public Health Preparedness and Response to Disasters |publisher=Jones & Bartlett Publishers |year=2013 |isbn=9781449645205 |page=210}}</ref> [[5&nbsp;World Trade Center]] was located at the northeast corner above the PATH station, and [[4 World Trade Center (1975-2001)|4&nbsp;World Trade Center]], located at the southeast corner,{{sfnp|Gillespie|1999|p=62}} housed the [[Commodities exchange|U.S. Commodities Exchange]].<ref name=Landesman/> In 1987, construction was completed on a 47-floor office building, [[7 World Trade Center]], located to the north of the superblock.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.panynj.gov/wtcprogress/history-wtc.html |title=History of the World Trade Center |work=Port Authority of New York and New Jersey |accessdate=May 26, 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150607110234/https://www.panynj.gov/wtcprogress/history-wtc.html |archive-date=June 7, 2015 |url-status=live}}</ref> Beneath the World Trade Center complex was an [[The Mall at the World Trade Center|underground shopping mall]]. It had connections to various mass transit facilities, including the [[New York City Subway]] system and the Port Authority's [[Port Authority Trans-Hudson|PATH]] trains.{{sfnp|Glanz|Lipton|2003|p=114}}{{sfnp|Gillespie|1999|p=217}}\n\nOne of the world's largest gold depositories was located underneath the World Trade Center, owned by a group of commercial banks. The 1993 bombing detonated close to the vault.<ref>[https://nymag.com/news/9-11/10th-anniversary/gold/ Gold, Recovery of The Towers' buried treasure] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150225013041/http://nymag.com/news/9-11/10th-anniversary/gold/ |date=February 25, 2015 }}, [[NY Mag]], {{Nowrap|August 27}}, 2011</ref> Seven weeks after the {{Nowrap|September 11}} attacks, $230&nbsp;million in precious metals was removed from basement vaults of 4&nbsp;WTC. This included 3,800 100-Troy-ounce 24 carat gold bars and 30,000 1,000-ounce silver bars.<ref>[http://www.rediff.com/money/2001/nov/17wtc.htm Rediff.com. Reuters, {{Nowrap|November 17}}, 2001: Buried WTC gold returns to futures trade] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924133903/http://www.rediff.com/money/2001/nov/17wtc.htm |date=September 24, 2015 }}. Retrieved {{Nowrap|December 1}}, 2008.</ref>\n\n==Major events==\n\n===February 13, 1975, fire===\nOn February 13, 1975, a [[three-alarm fire]] broke out on the 11th floor of the North Tower. It spread to the 9th and 14th floors after igniting telephone cable insulation in a utility shaft that ran vertically between floors. Areas at the furthest extent of the fire were extinguished almost immediately; the original fire was put out in a few hours. Most of the damage was concentrated on the 11th floor, fueled by cabinets filled with paper, alcohol-based fluid for office machines, and other office equipment. Fireproofing protected the steel and there was no structural damage to the tower. In addition to fire damage on the 9th through the 14th floors, the water used to extinguish the fire damaged a few of the floors below. At that time, the World Trade Center had no [[fire sprinkler system]]s.<ref name=\"nyt 19750214\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1975/02/14/nyregion/14WTC.html |title=Trade Center Hit by 6-Floor Fire |work=The New York Times |language=en-US |issn=0362-4331 |date=February 14, 1975 |accessdate=September 11, 2008 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080512074050/http://www.nytimes.com/1975/02/14/nyregion/14WTC.html |archive-date=May 12, 2008 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===February 26, 1993, bombing===\n{{Main|1993 World Trade Center bombing}}\n[[File:WTC 1993 ATF Commons.jpg|thumb|Aftermath of the 1993 bombing]]\nThe first terrorist attack on the World Trade Center occurred on February 26, 1993, at 12:17&nbsp;p.m. A [[Ryder]] truck filled with {{convert|1500|lb}} of explosives, planted by [[Ramzi Yousef]], detonated in the underground garage of the North Tower.<ref name=\"reeve p10\">{{cite book |last=Reeve |first=Simon |title=The new jackals : Ramzi Yousef, Osama Bin Laden and the future of terrorism |url=https://archive.org/details/newjackalsramziy00reev |url-access=registration |publisher=[[Northeastern University Press]] | location=Boston |year=2002 |isbn=978-1-55553-509-4 |page=[https://archive.org/details/newjackalsramziy00reev/page/10 10]}}</ref> The blast opened a 100-foot (30&nbsp;m) hole through five sublevels with the greatest damage occurring on levels B1 and B2 and significant structural damage on level B3.<ref>{{Cite book |title=Design, Construction, and Maintenance of Structural and Life Safety Systems (NCSTAR 1-1) |publisher=[[National Institute of Standards and Technology]] |pages=xlv |last=Lew |first=H.S. |author2=Richard W. Bukowski |author3=Nicholas J. Carino |date=September 2005}}</ref> Six people were killed, and 1,042 others were injured in the attacks, some from smoke inhalation.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.newsweek.com/id/111113 |title=A Shaken City's Towering Inferno |last=Mathews |first=Tom |date=March 8, 1993 |work=[[Newsweek]] |accessdate=October 26, 2008 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081030073528/http://www.newsweek.com/id/111113 |archive-date=October 30, 2008 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"barbanel\">{{Cite news |url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9F0CE5DC103DF934A15751C0A965958260&sec=&spon=&pagewanted=all |title=Tougher Code May Not Have Helped |last=Barbanel |first=Josh |date=February 27, 1993 |work=The New York Times |language=en-US |issn=0362-4331 |accessdate=November 20, 2008}}</ref> Sheikh [[Omar Abdel Rahman]]<ref name=\":0\" /> and four other individuals<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news |url=http://community.seattletimes.nwsource.com/archive/?date=19940525&slug=1912247 |title=In Sentencing Bombers, Judge Takes Hard Line |author1=Hays, Tom |date=May 25, 1994 |work=[[Seattle Times]] / AP |accessdate=November 20, 2008 |author2=Larry Neumeister |lastauthoramp=yes|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110626031815/http://community.seattletimes.nwsource.com/archive/?date=19940525&slug=1912247|archive-date=June 26, 2011|url-status=live}}</ref> were later convicted for their involvement in the bombing,<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news |url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9D0DE4DF1E39F93BA25752C0A960958260 |archive-url=https://archive.is/20120526191515/http://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9D0DE4DF1E39F93BA25752C0A960958260 |url-status=dead |archive-date=May 26, 2012 |title=Sheik Sentenced to Life in Prison in Bombing Plot |date=January 18, 1996 |last=Fried |first=Joseph P. |work=The New York Times |language=en-US |issn=0362-4331 |accessdate=November 20, 2008}}</ref><ref name=\":1\" /> while Yousef and [[Eyad Ismoil]] were convicted for carrying out the bombing.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://articles.cnn.com/1997-11-12/us/9711_12_world.trade.center_1_yousef-and-ismoil-bombing-plot-worst-terrorist-attack?_s=PM:US |title=Jury convicts 2 in Trade Center blast |publisher=CNN |date=November 12, 1997 |accessdate=November 20, 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100916042827/http://articles.cnn.com/1997-11-12/us/9711_12_world.trade.center_1_yousef-and-ismoil-bombing-plot-worst-terrorist-attack?_s=PM:US |archivedate=September 16, 2010 }}</ref> According to a presiding judge, the conspirators' chief aim at the time of the attack was to destabilize the north tower and send it crashing into the south tower, toppling both landmarks.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.cnn.com/US/9708/05/wtc.trial/index.html |title=Prosecutor: Yousef aimed to topple Trade Center towers |date=August 5, 1997 |publisher=CNN |accessdate=November 20, 2008 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081012085254/http://www.cnn.com/US/9708/05/wtc.trial/index.html |archive-date=October 12, 2008 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the bombing, floors that were blown out needed to be repaired to restore the structural support they provided to columns.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.interfire.org/res_file/pdf/Tr-076.pdf |title=The World Trade Center Complex |last=Port Authority Risk Management Staff |publisher=[[United States Fire Administration]] |accessdate=May 15, 2007 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070928113151/http://www.interfire.org/res_file/pdf/Tr-076.pdf |archive-date=September 28, 2007 |url-status=live}}</ref> The slurry wall was in peril following the bombing and loss of the floor slabs that provided lateral support against pressure from Hudson River water on the other side. The refrigeration plant on sublevel B5, which provided air conditioning to the entire World Trade Center complex, was heavily damaged.<ref name=\"ennala\">{{Cite journal |doi=10.1061/(ASCE)0887-3828(1994)8:4(229) |author1=Ramabhushanam, Ennala |author2=Marjorie Lynch |lastauthoramp=yes |title=Structural Assessment of Bomb Damage for World Trade Center |journal=Journal of Performance of Constructed Facilities |volume=8 |pages=229\u2013242 |issue=4 |year=1994}}</ref> After the bombing, the Port Authority installed [[photoluminescent]] pathway markings in the stairwells.<ref>{{Cite journal |url=http://www.fpemag.com/archives/enewsletter.asp?i=16 |title=Escape from New York \u2013 The Use of Photoluminescent Pathway-marking Systems in High-Rise |last=Amy |first=James D., Jr. |publisher=[[Society of Fire Protection Engineers]] |journal=Emerging Trends |date=December 2006 |volume=Issue 8 |accessdate=November 20, 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080117010033/http://www.fpemag.com/archives/enewsletter.asp?i=16 |archivedate=January 17, 2008}}</ref> The [[fire alarm system]] for the entire complex needed to be replaced because critical wiring and signaling in the original system were destroyed.<ref>{{Cite book |url=http://wtc.nist.gov/pubs/NISTNCSTAR1-4.pdf |title=Active Fire Protection Systems (NCSTAR 1\u20134) |publisher=National Institute of Standards and Technology |page=44 |last=Evans |first=David D. |author2=Richard D. Peacock |author3=Erica D. Kuligowski |author4=W. Stuart Dols |author5=William L. Grosshandler |date=September 2005 |access-date=March 11, 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110728081730/http://wtc.nist.gov/pubs/NISTNCSTAR1-4.pdf |archive-date=July 28, 2011 |url-status=live }}</ref> A memorial to the victims of the bombing, a [[reflecting pool]], was installed with the names of those who were killed in the blast.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://nytimes.com/2002/02/26/nyregion/their-monument-now-destroyed-1993-victims-are-remembered.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120914025508/http://www.nytimes.com/2002/02/26/nyregion/their-monument-now-destroyed-1993-victims-are-remembered.html |url-status=live |archive-date=September 14, 2012 |title=Their Monument Now Destroyed, 1993 Victims Are Remembered |last=Dwyer |first=Jim |work=The New York Times |language=en-US |issn=0362-4331 |date=February 26, 2002 |accessdate=November 20, 2008}}</ref> It was destroyed following the {{Nowrap|September 11}} attacks. The names of the victims of the 1993 bombing are included in the [[National September 11 Memorial & Museum]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Remembering the victims of the 1993 World Trade Center bombing |website=[[New York Daily News]] |date=February 13, 2018 |url=http://www.nydailynews.com/new-york/manhattan/remembering-victims-1993-world-trade-center-bombing-article-1.2983339 | access-date=February 25, 2018 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180226211614/http://www.nydailynews.com/new-york/manhattan/remembering-victims-1993-world-trade-center-bombing-article-1.2983339 | archive-date=February 26, 2018 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n===January 14, 1998, robbery===\n{{Main|1998 Bank of America robbery}}\n[[File:1995 New York World Trade Center - Karl D\u00f6ringer.jpg|thumb|Looking up at the World Trade Center from [[Austin J. Tobin#Legacy|Austin J. Tobin Plaza]], 1995|alt=]]\nIn January 1998, [[Italian-American Mafia|Mafia]] member [[Ralph Guarino]] gained maintenance access to the World Trade Center. He arranged a three-man crew for a heist that netted over $2&nbsp;million from a Brinks delivery to the 11th floor of the North Tower.<ref name=\"mafia 2007\">{{cite book |last=Reppetto |first=Thomas |title=Bringing down the mob : the war against the American Mafia |publisher=Henry Holt Melia distributor | location=New York Godalming |year=2007 |isbn=978-0-8050-8659-1 |page=279}}</ref>\n\n===Other events===\n\nOn the morning of August 7, 1974, [[Philippe Petit]] performed a high-wire walk between the North and South Towers of the World Trade Center. For his unauthorized feat {{convert|1,312|ft}} above the ground, he rigged a {{convert|440|lb|adj=on}} cable and used a custom-made {{convert|30|ft|m|adj=mid|-long}}, {{convert|55|lb|adj=on}} balancing pole. He performed for 45 minutes, making eight passes along the wire.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Lichtenstein|first=Grace|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1974/08/08/archives/stuntman-eluding-guards-walks-a-tightrope-between-trade-center.html|title=Stuntman, Eluding Guards, Walks a Tightrope Between Trade Center Towers|date=1974-08-08|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-02-21|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>  Though Petit was charged with criminal trespass and disorderly conduct, he was later freed in exchange for performing for children in [[Central Park]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1974/08/30/archives/aerialist-a-hit-in-central-park.html|title=Aerialist a Hit in Central Park|date=1974-08-30|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-02-21|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\nOn February 20, 1981, an [[Aerol\u00edneas Argentinas]] airliner was guided away by air traffic controllers after radar signals indicated it was on a collision course with the North Tower (1 WTC). The aircraft, which was scheduled to land at nearby [[John F. Kennedy International Airport|JFK Airport]], was flying at a much lower altitude than regulations recommended.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1981/02/27/nyregion/jet-crew-to-be-asked-about-near-miss.html |title=Jet Crew to be Asked about Near Miss |newspaper=The New York Times |language=en-US |issn=0362-4331 |accessdate=February 19, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180220033143/http://www.nytimes.com/1981/02/27/nyregion/jet-crew-to-be-asked-about-near-miss.html|archive-date=February 20, 2018|url-status=live|date=February 27, 1981 |last1=Witkin |first1=Richard }}</ref>\n\nThe [[Classical World Chess Championship 1995|1995 PCA world chess championship]] was played on the 107th floor of the South Tower.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=990CE3DA1230F93AA2575AC0A963958260 |last=Byrne |first=Robert |title=Kasparov Gets Pressure, but No Victory |work=The New York Times |language=en-US |issn=0362-4331 |accessdate=November 21, 2008 |date=September 19, 1995}}</ref>\n\n===Proposed lease===\nIn 1998, the Port Authority approved plans to privatize the World Trade Center,<ref>{{Cite news |title=PA to ease WTC tax load, rent would be cut to offset hike by city |newspaper=New York Daily News |date=February 6, 2001 |last=Herman |first=Eric}}</ref> and in 2001 sought to lease it to a private entity. Bids for the lease came from [[Vornado Realty Trust]], a joint bid between [[Brookfield Properties]] Corporation and [[Boston Properties]],<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9900E4DF163EF932A05752C0A9679C8B63 |title=Bidding for Twin Towers |work=The New York Times |language=en-US |issn=0362-4331 |date=January 31, 2001 |last=Bagli |first=Charles V. |accessdate=November 20, 2008}}</ref> and a joint bid by [[Silverstein Properties]] and [[The Westfield Group]].<ref name=\"cuozzo\">{{Cite news |title=Larry Lusts for Twin Towers; Silverstein has an Eye on WTC's; Untapped Retail Potential |newspaper=[[New York Post]] |date=January 30, 2001 |last=Cuozzo |first=Steve|author-link=Steve Cuozzo}}</ref> Privatizing the World Trade Center would add it to the city's tax rolls<ref name=\"cuozzo\" /> and provide funds for other Port Authority projects.<ref>{{Cite news |title=Port Authority Gets Final Bids on WTC |newspaper=New York Daily News |date=January 31, 2001 |last=Herman |first=Eric}}</ref> On {{Nowrap|February 15}}, 2001, the Port Authority announced that Vornado Realty Trust had won the lease for the World Trade Center, paying $3.25&nbsp;billion for the 99-year lease.<ref>{{Cite news |title=Brookfield Loses Lease Bid |newspaper=[[Toronto Star]] |date=February 23, 2001}}</ref> [[Vornado Realty Trust|Vornado]] outbid Silverstein by $600&nbsp;million though Silverstein upped his offer to $3.22&nbsp;billion. However, Vornado insisted on last minute changes to the deal, including a shorter 39-year lease, which the Port Authority considered nonnegotiable.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9A03E5DB113DF933A15750C0A9679C8B63&sec=&pagewanted=1a |title=As Trade Center Talks Stumble, No. 2 Bidder Gets Another Chance |last=Bagli |first=Charles V. |work=The New York Times |language=en-US |issn=0362-4331 |date=March 20, 2001 |accessdate=November 20, 2008 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080119031151/http://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9A03E5DB113DF933A15750C0A9679C8B63&sec=&pagewanted=1a |archive-date=January 19, 2008 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Vornado later withdrew and Silverstein's bid for the lease to the World Trade Center was accepted on {{Nowrap|April 26}}, 2001,<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9D01E3DA1339F934A15757C0A9679C8B63&sec=&pagewanted=1 |title=Deal Is Signed To Take Over Trade Center |last=Bagli |first=Charles V. |work=The New York Times |language=en-US |issn=0362-4331 |date=April 27, 2001 |accessdate=November 20, 2008 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090222154850/http://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9D01E3DA1339F934A15757C0A9679C8B63&sec=&pagewanted=1 |archive-date=February 22, 2009 |url-status=dead }}</ref> and closed on {{Nowrap|July 24}}, 2001.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9B06E0D91F3AF936A15754C0A9679C8B63&sec=&spon= |title=Leasing of Trade Center May Help Transit Projects, Pataki Says |work=The New York Times |language=en-US |issn=0362-4331 |date=July 25, 2001 |last=Smothers |first=Ronald |accessdate=November 20, 2008 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080517112948/http://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9B06E0D91F3AF936A15754C0A9679C8B63&sec=&spon= |archive-date=May 17, 2008 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==Destruction==\n{{Main|September 11 attacks|Collapse of the World Trade Center}}\n[[File:UA Flight 175 hits WTC south tower 9-11 edit.jpeg|thumb|A fireball rises in the immediate aftermath of United Airlines Flight 175 hitting the South Tower during the [[September 11 attacks]].]]\nOn [[September 11 attacks|September 11, 2001]], Islamist terrorists hijacked [[American Airlines Flight 11]] and crashed it into the northern fa\u00e7ade of the North Tower <ref name=\"Moghadam\">{{cite book|title=The Globalization of Martyrdom: Al Qaeda, Salafi Jihad, and the Diffusion of Suicide Attacks|last=Moghadam|first=Assaf|publisher=Johns Hopkins University|year=2008|isbn=978-0-8018-9055-0|page=48}}</ref> at 8:46:40&nbsp;a.m.; the aircraft struck between the 93rd and 99th floors. Seventeen minutes later, at 9:03:11&nbsp;a.m., a second group crashed the similarly hijacked [[United Airlines Flight 175]] into the southern fa\u00e7ade of the South Tower, striking it between the 77th and 85th floors.<ref name=\"911commission\">{{cite web |title=The 9/11 Commission Report |url=http://govinfo.library.unt.edu/911/report/911Report.pdf#page=302 |publisher=[[9/11 Commission|National Commission on Terrorist Attacks Upon the United States]] |date=July 27, 2004 |accessdate=September 29, 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110208154444/http://govinfo.library.unt.edu/911/report/911Report.pdf#page=302 |archive-date=February 8, 2011 |url-status=live}}</ref> The damage caused to the North Tower by Flight 11 destroyed any means of escape from above the impact zone, trapping 1,344 people.<ref name=\"102Mins\">{{cite news |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5bTftBx4s?url=http://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9F00E6DC153BF935A15756C0A9649C8B63&sec=&spon=&pagewanted=4 |archivedate=October 11, 2008 |last=Dwyer |first=Jim |author2=Lipton, Eric |title=102 Minutes: Last Words at the Trade Center; Fighting to Live as the Towers Die |url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9F00E6DC153BF935A15756C0A9649C8B63&sec=&spon=&pagewanted=4 |date=May 26, 2002 |work=The New York Times |language=en-US |issn=0362-4331 |accessdate=May 23, 2008 |display-authors=etal |url-status=live }}</ref> Flight 175 had a much more off-centered impact compared to Flight 11, and a single stairwell was left intact; however, only a few people managed to descend successfully before the tower collapsed. Although the South Tower was struck lower than the North Tower, thus affecting more floors, a smaller number, fewer than 700, were killed instantly or trapped.<ref name=\"NYTFatal\">{{Cite news |last=Lipton |first=Eric |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2004/07/22/nyregion/study-maps-the-location-of-deaths-in-the-twin-towers.html |title=Study Maps the Location of Deaths in the Twin Towers |date=July 22, 2004 |work=The New York Times |language=en-US |issn=0362-4331 |accessdate=August 12, 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150528044535/http://www.nytimes.com/2004/07/22/nyregion/study-maps-the-location-of-deaths-in-the-twin-towers.html |archive-date=May 28, 2015 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nAt 9:59&nbsp;a.m., the South Tower [[collapse of the World Trade Center|collapsed]] after burning for approximately 56 minutes. The fire caused steel structural elements, already weakened from the plane's impact, to fail. The North Tower collapsed at 10:28&nbsp;a.m., after burning for approximately 102&nbsp;minutes.{{sfnp|NIST NCSTAR 1-1|2005|pp=34, 45\u201346}} At 5:20&nbsp;p.m.<ref name=\"ch5\" /> on {{Nowrap|September 11}}, 2001, 7 World Trade Center began to collapse with the crumbling of the east penthouse; it collapsed completely at 5:21&nbsp;p.m.<ref name=\"ch5\">{{harvp|ps=.|World Trade Center Building Performance Study|2002|pages=5.23 to 5. 24}}</ref> owing to uncontrolled fires causing structural failure.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://wtc.nist.gov/media/NIST_NCSTAR_1A_for_public_comment.pdf |title=Final Report on the Collapse of World Trade Center Building 7 \u2013 Draft for Public Comment |publisher=NIST |pages=xxxii |date=August 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080928013317/http://wtc.nist.gov/media/NIST_NCSTAR_1A_for_public_comment.pdf |archivedate=September 28, 2008 }}</ref>\n\n[[File:World Trade Center 3 After 9-11 Attacks With Original Building Locations.jpg|thumb|[[World Trade Center site]] after 9/11 attacks, seen from above with original building locations outlined in yellow]]\n\nThe Marriott World Trade Center hotel was destroyed during the collapse of the two towers. The three remaining buildings in the WTC plaza were extensively damaged by debris and were later demolished.<ref name=\"wtcstudy\">{{harvp|World Trade Center Building Performance Study|2002|pages=3.1, 4.1}}</ref> The [[Rescue and recovery effort after the September 11 attacks|cleanup and recovery process]] at the [[World Trade Center site]] took eight months.<ref>{{cite news |title=The Last Steel Column |url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9F02E4D71E3BF933A05756C0A9649C8B63 |archive-url=https://archive.is/20130130073734/http://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9F02E4D71E3BF933A05756C0A9649C8B63 |url-status=dead |archive-date=January 30, 2013 |newspaper=The New York Times |language=en-US |issn=0362-4331 |date=May 30, 2002 |accessdate=July 31, 2010}}</ref> The [[Deutsche Bank Building]] across Liberty Street from the World Trade Center complex was later condemned because of the uninhabitable toxic conditions inside; it was deconstructed, with work completed in early 2011.{{sfnp|World Trade Center Building Performance Study|2002|page=6.1}}<ref>{{cite web |title=The Deutsche Bank Building at 130&nbsp;Liberty Street |publisher=Lower Manhattan Construction Command Center |url=http://www.renewnyc.com/plan_des_dev/130Liberty/default.asp |accessdate=July 12, 2007 |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/61DZN1B92?url=http://www.renewnyc.com/plan_des_dev/130Liberty/default.asp |archive-date=August 26, 2011 |url-status=live}}</ref> The [[Borough of Manhattan Community College]]'s Fiterman Hall at 30 [[West Broadway (Manhattan)|West Broadway]] was also condemned owing to extensive damage, and it was demolished and completely rebuilt.<ref>{{cite web |last=Shapiro |first=Julie |title=Students Return to Rebuilt Fiterman Hall 11 Years After 9/11 |website=DNAinfo New York |date=August 27, 2012 |url=https://www.dnainfo.com/new-york/20120827/financial-district/students-return-rebuilt-fiterman-hall-11-years-after-911 | access-date=October 27, 2017 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171027125835/https://www.dnainfo.com/new-york/20120827/financial-district/students-return-rebuilt-fiterman-hall-11-years-after-911 |archivedate=October 27, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn the immediate aftermath of the attacks, media reports suggested that tens of thousands might have been killed in the attacks, as over 50,000 people could have been inside the World Trade Center. The [[National Institute of Standards and Technology]] (NIST) estimated approximately 17,400 individuals were in the towers at the time of the attacks.<ref>{{Cite book |last=Averill |first=Jason D. |chapter-url=http://wtc.nist.gov/NISTNCSTAR1-7.pdf |chapter=Occupant Behavior, Egress, and Emergency Communications |title=Final Reports of the Federal Building and Fire Investigation of the World Trade Center Disaster |publisher=National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST) |year=2005|display-authors=etal|access-date=January 7, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090714130213/http://wtc.nist.gov/NISTNCSTAR1-7.pdf|archive-date=July 14, 2009|url-status=live }}</ref> Ultimately, 2,753 death certificates (excluding those for hijackers) were filed relating to the 9/11 attacks.<!-- including one filed for Felicia Dunn-Jones, who was added to the official death toll in {{Nowrap|May 2007}}; Dunn-Jones died five months later from a lung condition linked to exposure to dust during the collapse of the World Trade Center.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2007/05/24/nyregion/24dust.html |title=For the First Time, New York Links a Death to 9/11 Dust |last=DePalma |first=Anthony |work=The New York Times |language=en-US |issn=0362-4331 |date=May 24, 2007 |access-date=February 23, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170327032459/http://www.nytimes.com/2007/05/24/nyregion/24dust.html |archive-date=March 27, 2017 |url-status=live}}</ref> Three other victims were then added to the official death toll by the city medical examiner's office: [[Sneha Anne Philip|Dr. Sneha Anne Philip]], who was last seen the day before the attacks; Leon Heyward, a man who developed lymphoma and subsequently died in 2008 as a result of dust ingestion during the events following the attacks to the Twin Towers;<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.cbsnews.com/stories/2008/07/10/national/main4250100.shtml |title=Official 9/11 Death Toll Climbs By One |work=[[CBS News]] |agency=[[Associated Press]] |date=July 10, 2008 |accessdate=August 29, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100824172030/http://www.cbsnews.com/stories/2008/07/10/national/main4250100.shtml |archive-date=August 24, 2010 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/09/12/nyregion/12groundzero.html |title=9/11's Litany of Loss, Joined by Another Name |newspaper=The New York Times |language=en-US |issn=0362-4331 |date=September 11, 2009 |accessdate=August 29, 2010 |first=Lisa W. |last=Foderaro |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110501025734/http://www.nytimes.com/2009/09/12/nyregion/12groundzero.html |archive-date=May 1, 2011 |url-status=live}}</ref> and Jerry Borg, who died in December 2010 of [[pulmonary sarcoidosis]] determined in June 2011 to be the result of dust from the attacks.<ref name=\"Borg\"/> NB: Have hidden this text. It seems like unnecessary detail for an article on a building complex---> 2,192 [[civilian]]s died in and around the World Trade Center, including<!--658---> employees of [[Cantor Fitzgerald|Cantor Fitzgerald L.P.]] (an investment bank on the 101st\u2013105th floors of One World Trade Center),<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/americas/5282060.stm |title=Cantor rebuilds after 9/11 losses |work=BBC News |location=London |date=September 4, 2006 |accessdate=May 20, 2008 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080407091157/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/americas/5282060.stm |archive-date=April 7, 2008 |url-status=live}}</ref> <!--295 employees of---> [[Marsh & McLennan Companies]] (located immediately below Cantor Fitzgerald on floors 93\u2013101, the location of Flight 11's impact), and <!--175 employees of--->  [[Aon Corporation]].<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.investmentnews.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20070911/REG/70911011 |title=Industry honors fallen on 9/11 anniversary |work=InvestmentNews |last=Siegel |first=Aaron |date=September 11, 2007 |accessdate=May 20, 2008 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070915130042/http://www.investmentnews.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=%2F20070911%2FREG%2F70911011 |archive-date=September 15, 2007 |url-status=live}}</ref> In addition to the civilian deaths, 414 [[Emergency workers killed in the September 11 attacks|sworn personnel]] were also killed: 340 [[New York City Fire Department]] (FDNY) [[firefighter]]s; 71 [[law enforcement officer]]s, including 37 members of the [[Port Authority Police Department]] (PAPD) and 23 members of the [[New York City Police Department]] (NYPD); 2 [[New York City Fire Department Bureau of EMS|FDNY paramedics]]; and 1 FDNY [[chaplain]]. Eight [[Emergency medical services|EMS]] personnel from private agencies also died in the attacks.<ref>{{Cite news |first1=Denise |last1=Grady |first2=Andrew C. |last2=Revkin |title=Lung Ailments May Force 500 Firefighters Off Job |url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9C05E1DC1631F933A2575AC0A9649C8B63 |date=September 10, 2002 |work=The New York Times |language=en-US |issn=0362-4331 |accessdate=May 23, 2008}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |title=Post-9/11 report recommends police, fire response changes |url=https://www.usatoday.com/news/nation/2002-08-19-nypd-nyfd-report_x.htm |date=August 19, 2002 |agency=Associated Press |newspaper=[[USA Today]] |location=Washington DC |accessdate=May 23, 2008 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110820043759/http://www.usatoday.com/news/nation/2002-08-19-nypd-nyfd-report_x.htm |archive-date=August 20, 2011 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |title=Police back on day-to-day beat after 9/11 nightmare |url=http://archives.cnn.com/2002/US/07/20/wtc.police/index.html |date=July 21, 2002 |publisher=CNN |accessdate=May 23, 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080517155430/http://archives.cnn.com/2002/US/07/20/wtc.police/index.html |archivedate=May 17, 2008}}</ref> Ten years after the attacks, the remains of only 1,629 victims had been identified.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.nydailynews.com/ny_local/2011/08/24/2011-08-24_id_remains_of_wtc_worker_10_yrs_later.html |title=Remains of WTC worker Ernest James, 40, ID'd ten years after 9/11 |last=Lemre |first=Jonathan |work=New York Daily News |date=August 24, 2011 |accessdate=August 25, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110824224635/http://www.nydailynews.com/ny_local/2011/08/24/2011-08-24_id_remains_of_wtc_worker_10_yrs_later.html |archive-date=August 24, 2011 |url-status=live}}</ref> Of all the people who were still in the towers when they collapsed, only 20 were pulled out alive.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://m.rockymountainnews.com/news/2006/aug/04/terror-in-close-up/ |title=Terror in close-up |last=Denerstein |first=Robert |location=Denver, CO |date=August 4, 2006 |newspaper=[[Rocky Mountain News]] |accessdate=November 19, 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130730120308/http://m.rockymountainnews.com/news/2006/aug/04/terror-in-close-up/ |archivedate=July 30, 2013 }}</ref>\n{{clear}}\n\n==New World Trade Center==\n{{Planned World Trade Center}}\n{{Main|World Trade Center (2001\u2013present)}}\n\nOver the following years, plans were created for the reconstruction of the World Trade Center. The [[Lower Manhattan Development Corporation]] (LMDC), established in {{Nowrap|November 2001}} to oversee the rebuilding process,<ref>{{cite news |last=P\u00e9rez-Pe\u00f1a |first=Richard |title=A Nation Challenged; Downtown; State Plans Rebuilding Agency, Perhaps Led by Giuliani |url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=950DEFD81639F930A35752C1A9679C8B63 |newspaper=The New York Times |language=en-US |issn=0362-4331 |date=November 3, 2001 |accessdate=July 31, 2010}}</ref> organized competitions to select a [[site plan]] and memorial design.<ref>{{cite news |title=Up From The Ashes |publisher=Newsweek |date=November 12, 2001 |last=McGuigan |first=Cathleen}}</ref> [[Memory Foundations]], designed by [[Daniel Libeskind]], was selected as the master plan;<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.renewnyc.com/plan_des_dev/wtc_site/new_design_plans/Sept_2003_refined_design.asp |title=Refined Master Site Plan for the World Trade Center Site |work=[[Lower Manhattan Development Corporation]] |accessdate=May 1, 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140416100733/http://www.renewnyc.com/plan_des_dev/wtc_site/new_design_plans/Sept_2003_refined_design.asp |archive-date=April 16, 2014 |url-status=live}}</ref> however, substantial changes were made to the design.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://cityroom.blogs.nytimes.com/2012/06/12/1-world-trade-center-is-a-growing-presence-and-a-changed-one/ |title=1 World Trade Center Is a Growing Presence, and a Changed One |first=David W. |last=Dunlap |work=The New York Times |language=en-US |issn=0362-4331 |date=June 12, 2012 |accessdate=December 9, 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151027062933/http://cityroom.blogs.nytimes.com/2012/06/12/1-world-trade-center-is-a-growing-presence-and-a-changed-one/ |archive-date=October 27, 2015 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n[[File:WTCmemorialJune2012.png|thumb|left|The National September 11 Memorial. The reflecting pools are on the [[World Trade Center site|site of the Twin Towers.]]]]\n\nThe first new building at the site was 7&nbsp;WTC, which opened on {{Nowrap|May 23, 2006}}.<ref name=\"lowermanhattan.info\">{{cite web |url=http://www.lowermanhattan.info/news/7_world_trade_center_50451.aspx |title=7 World Trade Center Opens with Musical Fanfare |publisher=Lower Manhattan Development Corporation (LMDC) |date=May 22, 2006 |accessdate=July 27, 2007 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070809115805/http://www.lowermanhattan.info/news/7_world_trade_center_50451.aspx |archivedate=August 9, 2007 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The memorial section of the [[National September 11 Memorial & Museum]] opened on September 11, 2011,<ref>{{cite web |title=Public Gets First Glimpse Of 9/11 Memorial |url=http://www.ny1.com/content/top_stories/146985/public-gets-first-glimpse-of-9-11-memorial |archive-url=https://archive.is/20120905095351/http://www.ny1.com/content/top_stories/146985/public-gets-first-glimpse-of-9-11-memorial |url-status=dead |archive-date=September 5, 2012 |last=[[NY1]] News |date=September 12, 2011 |accessdate=September 12, 2011}}</ref> and the museum opened on May 21, 2014.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.myfoxny.com/story/25574078/national-september-11-memorial-museum-opens |title=National September 11 Memorial Museum opens |work=Fox NY |date=May 21, 2014 |accessdate=May 21, 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140521194934/http://www.myfoxny.com/story/25574078/national-september-11-memorial-museum-opens |archivedate=May 21, 2014}}</ref> 1&nbsp;WTC opened on {{nowrap|November 3}}, 2014;<ref name=\"yahoo\">{{cite news |url=https://news.yahoo.com/world-trade-center-reopens-business-071956091.html |title=World Trade Center Reopens for Business |agency=Associated Press |accessdate=November 3, 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141103191607/http://news.yahoo.com/world-trade-center-reopens-business-071956091.html |archive-date=November 3, 2014 |url-status=live}}</ref> 4&nbsp;WTC opened on {{nowrap|November 13}}, 2013;<ref name=\"Wtc.com\">{{cite web |url=http://www.wtc.com/ |title=&#124;&#124; World Trade Center &#124;&#124; |publisher=Wtc.com |date=December 31, 2013 |accessdate=February 3, 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080909162202/http://www.wtc.com/ |archive-date=September 9, 2008 |url-status=live}}</ref> and 3&nbsp;WTC opened on June 11, 2018.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://commercialobserver.com/2018/06/inside-3-world-trade-center-opens/ |title=3 World Trade Center Opens Today: Here's a Look Inside |date=June 11, 2018 |work=[[Commercial Observer]]|access-date=June 11, 2018 |language=en-US|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180612141512/https://commercialobserver.com/2018/06/inside-3-world-trade-center-opens/|archive-date=June 12, 2018|url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nIn November 2013, according to an agreement made with Silverstein Properties Inc., the new 2&nbsp;WTC would not be built to its full height until sufficient space was leased to make the building financially viable.<ref>{{cite news |title=NYC's World Trade Tower Opens 40% Empty in Revival |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/2013-11-12/world-trade-center-tower-debuts-in-manhattan-leasing-test.html |accessdate=February 22, 2014 |newspaper=[[Bloomberg News]] |date=November 12, 2013 |first=David M. |last=Levitt |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140204171817/http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2013-11-12/world-trade-center-tower-debuts-in-manhattan-leasing-test.html |archive-date=February 4, 2014 |url-status=live}}</ref> Above-ground construction of 5&nbsp;WTC was also suspended due to a lack of tenants<ref>{{cite web |url=http://jewishbusinessnews.com/2013/11/12/new-world-trade-center-coming-to-life-already-impacts-new-york-skyline/ |title=New World Trade Center Coming To Life Already Impacts New York Skyline |last=Minchom |first=Clive |date=November 12, 2013 |website=[[Jewish Business News]] |accessdate=October 5, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151006031825/http://jewishbusinessnews.com/2013/11/12/new-world-trade-center-coming-to-life-already-impacts-new-york-skyline/|archive-date=October 6, 2015|url-status=live }}</ref> as well as disputes between the Port Authority and the Lower Manhattan Development Corporation.<ref>{{cite web |title=The looming World Trade Center 'stalemate' |website=Downtown Express |date=September 11, 2014 |url=http://www.downtownexpress.com/2014/09/11/the-looming-world-trade-center-stalemate/ | access-date=November 25, 2017 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171201033819/http://www.downtownexpress.com/2014/09/11/the-looming-world-trade-center-stalemate/ | archive-date=December 1, 2017 | url-status=live }}</ref> In mid-2015, Silverstein Properties revealed plans for a redesigned 2&nbsp;WTC, to be designed by [[Bjarke Ingels]] and completed by 2020 with [[News Corp (2013\u2013present)|News Corp]] as anchor tenant.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://wtc.com/office-space/2-world-trade-center#leasingAnchor |title=2 World Trade Center Office Space \u2013 World Trade Center |access-date=September 27, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151006001059/http://www.wtc.com/office-space/2-world-trade-center#leasingAnchor|archive-date=October 6, 2015|url-status=live }}</ref> Four years later, with no anchor tenant for 2&nbsp;WTC, Silverstein expressed his intent to resume work on the tower regardless of whether a tenant had signed.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2019-02-11/silverstein-eyes-building-final-wtc-tower-without-signed-tenant |title=Silverstein May Start Building Final WTC Tower Without Signed Tenant |last=Katz |first=Lily |date=February 11, 2019 |website=Bloomberg|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190222041822/https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2019-02-11/silverstein-eyes-building-final-wtc-tower-without-signed-tenant|archive-date=February 22, 2019|url-status=live|access-date=February 21, 2019}}</ref>\n\n{{Clear}}\n\n==Impact==\n===On the surrounding community===\n[[File:The World Trade Center in New York City, July 28, 2000.jpg|thumb|The World Trade Center, as seen from a nearby street in 2000]]\nThe original World Trade Center created a superblock that cut through the area's street grid, isolating the complex from the rest of the community.<ref name=\"Nobel 2005 54\" /><ref name=\"NYTimes-WTCSite-Intersection-2014\">{{cite web |last=Dunlap |first=David W. |title=At World Trade Center Site, Rebuilding Recreates Intersection of Long Ago |website=The New York Times |language=en-US |issn=0362-4331 |date=August 1, 2014 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/08/01/nyregion/rebuilding-recreates-intersection-of-long-ago.html | access-date=February 23, 2018 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180228161540/https://www.nytimes.com/2014/08/01/nyregion/rebuilding-recreates-intersection-of-long-ago.html | archive-date=February 28, 2018 | url-status=live }}</ref>{{sfnp|Glanz|Lipton|2003|p=64}} The Port Authority had demolished several streets to make way for the towers within the World Trade Center. The project involved combining the twelve-block area bounded by Vesey, Church, Liberty, and West Streets on the north, east, south, and west, respectively.<ref name=\"NYTimes-WTCSite-Intersection-2014\" />{{sfnp|Glanz|Lipton|2003|p=65}} 7 World Trade Center, built on the superblock's north side in the late 1980s, was built over another block of Greenwich Street. The building acted as a physical barrier separating Tribeca to the north and the Financial District to the south.<ref>{{cite book |last=Sagalyn |first=L.B. |title=Power at Ground Zero: Politics, Money, and the Remaking of Lower Manhattan |publisher=[[Oxford University Press]] |year=2016 |isbn=978-0-19-060704-3 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=gzDKDAAAQBAJ&pg=PT125 | access-date=February 23, 2018 |page=125}}</ref> The underground mall at the World Trade Center also drew shoppers away from surrounding streets.<ref name=\"NYTimes-Galleria-2005\" />\n\nThe project was seen as being monolithic and overambitious,<ref>{{cite journal |journal=CTBUH Journal |publisher=[[Council on Tall Buildings and Urban Habitat]] |url=http://www.ctbuh.org/LinkClick.aspx?fileticket=vL09f9r%2BT4s%3D&tabid=2684&language=en-US |title=Planning the World Trade Center 40 Years Apart |last=Klerks |first=Jan |issue=3 |year=2011 |page=29|access-date=March 1, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160729003316/http://ctbuh.org/LinkClick.aspx?fileticket=vL09f9r%2bT4s%3d&tabid=2684&language=en-US|archive-date=July 29, 2016|url-status=live }}</ref> with the design having had no public input.<ref name=\"CNU 2002\">{{cite web |title=WTC will be test for urbanism |website=CNU |date=September 1, 2002 |url=https://www.cnu.org/publicsquare/2002/09/01/wtc-will-be-test-urbanism | access-date=February 23, 2018 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180228161541/https://www.cnu.org/publicsquare/2002/09/01/wtc-will-be-test-urbanism | archive-date=February 28, 2018 | url-status=live }}</ref> By contrast, the rebuilding plans had significant public input.<ref>{{cite web |title=Ground Zero - The Stakeholders - Sacred Ground - FRONTLINE |website=PBS |date=July 4, 2004 |url=https://www.pbs.org/wgbh/pages/frontline/shows/sacred/designs/stakeholders.html | access-date=February 23, 2018 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180301164448/https://www.pbs.org/wgbh/pages/frontline/shows/sacred/designs/stakeholders.html | archive-date=March 1, 2018 | url-status=live }}</ref> The public supported rebuilding a street grid through the World Trade Center site.<ref name=\"CNU 2002\" /><ref name=\"NYTimes-WTCSite-Intersection-2014\" /><ref>{{cite book |last=Greenspan |first=E. |title=Battle for Ground Zero: Inside the Political Struggle to Rebuild the World Trade Center |publisher=[[St. Martin's Press]] |year=2013 |isbn=978-0-230-34138-8 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=OTYtAAAAQBAJ&pg=PA121 | access-date=February 23, 2018 |page=121}}</ref> One of the rebuilding proposals included building an enclosed shopping street along the path of [[Cortlandt Street (Manhattan)|Cortlandt Street]], one of the streets demolished to make room for the original World Trade Center.<ref name=\"NYTimes-Galleria-2005\">{{cite web |last=Dunlap |first=David W. |title=Does Putting Up a Glass Galleria Count as Bringing Back a Street? |website=The New York Times |language=en-US |issn=0362-4331 |date=November 24, 2005 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2005/11/24/nyregion/does-putting-up-a-glass-galleria-count-as-bringing-back-a-street.html | access-date=February 23, 2018 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180301164557/http://www.nytimes.com/2005/11/24/nyregion/does-putting-up-a-glass-galleria-count-as-bringing-back-a-street.html | archive-date=March 1, 2018 | url-status=live }}</ref> However, the Port Authority ultimately decided to rebuild Cortlandt, [[Fulton Street (Manhattan)|Fulton]], and [[Greenwich Street]]s, which had been destroyed during the original World Trade Center's construction.<ref name=\"NYTimes-WTCSite-Intersection-2014\" />\n\n===As an icon of popular culture===\n{{Main|World Trade Center in popular culture}}\n\n[[File:World Trade Center 1995.jpg|thumb|The World Trade Center, as seen from [[Liberty Island]] in 1995]]\n\nBefore its destruction, the World Trade Center was a New York City icon, and the Twin Towers were the centerpiece that represented the entire complex. They were used in film and TV projects as \"[[establishing shot]]s\", standing for New York City as a whole.{{sfnp|Langmead|2009|p=353}} In 1999, one writer noted: \"Nearly every guidebook in New York City lists the Twin Towers among the city's top ten attractions.\"{{sfnp|Gillespie|1999|p=162}}\n\nThere were several high-profile events that occurred at the World Trade Center. The most notable was held at the original WTC in 1974. French high wire acrobatic performer [[Philippe Petit]] walked between the two towers on a tightrope,{{sfnp|Glanz|Lipton|2003|p=219}} as shown in the documentary film ''[[Man on Wire]]'' (2008)<ref>{{cite news |title=Wire-walk film omits 9/11 tragedy |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/7498364.stm |publisher=BBC News |date=August 2, 2008|access-date=February 28, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180721193041/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/7498364.stm|archive-date=July 21, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> and depicted in the feature film ''[[The Walk (2015 film)|The Walk]]'' (2015).<ref>{{cite news |last=McNarry |first=Dave |title=Joseph Gordon-Levitt's 'The Walk' Running Early at Imax Locations |url=https://variety.com/2015/film/news/joseph-gordon-levitt-the-walk-imax-1201528806/ |magazine=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |publisher=([[Penske Media Corporation]]) |date=June 25, 2015 |accessdate=June 26, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150626193820/http://variety.com/2015/film/news/joseph-gordon-levitt-the-walk-imax-1201528806/|archive-date=June 26, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> Petit walked between the towers eight times on a steel cable.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.thedailybeast.com/newsweek/2008/07/18/he-had-new-york-at-his-feet.html |title=He Had New York At His Feet |accessdate=March 11, 2015 |url-status=dead |work=The Daily Beast |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130901032007/http://www.thedailybeast.com/newsweek/2008/07/18/he-had-new-york-at-his-feet.html |archivedate=September 1, 2013}}</ref>{{sfnp|Glanz|Lipton|2003|p=219}} In 1975, [[Owen J. Quinn]] base-jumped from the roof of the North Tower and safely landed on the plaza between the buildings.{{sfn|Gillespie|1999|pages=142\u2013143}} Quinn claimed that he was trying to publicize the plight of the poor.{{sfn|Gillespie|1999|pages=142\u2013143}} In 1977, Brooklyn toymaker [[George Willig]] scaled the exterior of the [[2 World Trade Center|South Tower]]. He later said, \"It looked unscalable; I thought I'd like to try it.\"{{sfnp|Gillespie|1999|p=149}}{{sfnp|Glanz|Lipton|2003|p=218}} Six years later, high-rise firefighting and rescue advocate [[Dan Goodwin]] successfully climbed the outside of the North Tower to call attention to the inability to rescue people potentially trapped in the upper floors of skyscrapers.<ref>{{cite journal |date=February 1989 |title=Skyscrapers |journal=[[National Geographic]] |page=169}}</ref><ref name=\"Skyscraper Defense\">{{cite web |url=http://www.skyscraperdefense.com/building_climbs.html |title=Skyscraper Defense |accessdate=July 4, 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110716083034/http://www.skyscraperdefense.com/building_climbs.html|archive-date=July 16, 2011|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe complex was featured in numerous works of popular culture; in 2006, it was estimated that the World Trade Center had appeared in some form in 472 films.{{sfnp|Langmead|2009|p=353}} Several iconic meanings were attributed to the World Trade Center. Film critic [[David Sterritt]], who lived near the complex, said that the World Trade Center's appearance in the 1978 film ''[[Superman (1978 film)|Superman]]'' \"summarized a certain kind of American grandeur [...] the grandeur, I would say, of sheer American powerfulness\". Remarking on the towers' destruction in the 1996 film ''[[Independence Day (1996 film)|Independence Day]]'', Sterritt said, \"The Twin Towers have been destroyed in various disaster movies that were made before 9/11. That became something that you couldn't do even retroactively after 9/11.\" Other motifs included romance, depicted in the 1988 film ''[[Working Girl (film)|Working Girl]]'', and corporate avarice, depicted in ''[[Wall Street (1987 film)|Wall Street]]'' (1987) and ''[[The Bonfire of the Vanities]]'' (1987).<ref>{{cite news |last=Poulou |first=Penelope |title=New York's Twin Towers Appear in Many Hollywood Films |url=https://www.voanews.com/a/new-yorks-twin-towers-appear-in-many-hollywood-films-128592413/165032.html |publisher=[[Voice of America]] |website=VOANews.com |date=August 29, 2011|access-date=February 28, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180301164507/https://www.voanews.com/a/new-yorks-twin-towers-appear-in-many-hollywood-films-128592413/165032.html|archive-date=March 1, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> Comic books, animated cartoons, television shows, video games, and music videos also used the complex as a setting.{{sfnp|Langmead|2009|p=354}}\n\n==== After the September 11 attacks ====\n{{see also|List of entertainment affected by the September 11 attacks|List of cultural references to the September 11 attacks}}\nAfter the September 11 attacks, some movies and TV shows [[Cultural influence of the September 11 attacks|deleted scenes or episodes]] set within the World Trade Center.<ref name=\"Mashberg 2019\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/09/10/movies/9-11-twin-towers-tv-movies.html|title=After Sept. 11, Twin Towers Onscreen Are a Tribute and a Painful Reminder|last=Mashberg|first=Tom|date=September 10, 2019|work=The New York Times|access-date=September 13, 2019|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref name=\"EW.com 2013\">{{cite news |last=Bahr |first=Lindsay |title=Television's uneasy relationship with the World Trade Center |url=https://ew.com/article/2013/01/21/televisions-uneasy-relationship-with-the-world-trade-center/ |magazine=[[Entertainment Weekly]] |date=January 21, 2013|access-date=February 23, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180226153248/http://ew.com/article/2013/01/21/televisions-uneasy-relationship-with-the-world-trade-center/|archive-date=February 26, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Lemire |first=Christy |title=Twin towers erased from some films after 9/11 |url=http://www.today.com/id/44206574/ns/today-today_entertainment/t/twin-towers-erased-some-films-after/ |publisher=[[NBC News]] |website=Today.com |date=September 13, 2011|access-date=November 9, 2018 |language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181109133908/http://www.today.com/id/44206574/ns/today-today_entertainment/t/twin-towers-erased-some-films-after/|archive-date=November 9, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>{{sfnp|Dixon|2004|p=4}} For example, ''[[The Simpsons]]'' episode \"[[The City of New York vs. Homer Simpson]]\", which first aired in 1997, was removed from syndication after the attacks because a scene showed the World Trade Center.<ref>{{cite news |last=Snierson |first=Dan |title='Simpsons' exec producer Al Jean: 'I completely understand' if reruns with nuclear jokes are pulled |url=https://ew.com/article/2011/03/27/simpsons-al-jean-nuclear-japan/ |magazine=Entertainment Weekly |date=March 27, 2011|access-date=November 9, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180708205626/http://ew.com/article/2011/03/27/simpsons-al-jean-nuclear-japan/|archive-date=July 8, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> Songs that mentioned the World Trade Center were no longer aired on radio, and the release dates of some films, such as the 2001\u20132002 films ''[[Sidewalks of New York (2001 film)|Sidewalks of New York]], [[People I Know]],'' and [[Spider-Man (2002 film)|''Spider-Man'']], were delayed so producers could remove scenes that included the World Trade Center.<ref name=\"Mashberg 2019\" />{{sfnp|Langmead|2009|p=354}} The 2001 film ''[[Kissing Jessica Stein]]'', which was shown at the [[Toronto International Film Festival]] the day before the attacks, had to be modified before its general public release, so the filmmakers could delete the scenes that depicted the World Trade Center.<ref name=\"Mashberg 2019\" />\n\nOther episodes and films mentioned the attacks directly, or depicted the World Trade Center in alternate contexts.<ref name=\"EW.com 2013\" /> The production of some family-oriented films was also sped up due to a large demand for that genre following the attacks. Demand for horror and action films decreased, but within a short time demand returned to normal.{{sfnp|Dixon|2004|p=4}} By the first anniversary of the attacks, over sixty \"memorial films\" had been created.{{sfnp|Dixon|2004|p=5}} Filmmakers were criticized for removing scenes related to the World Trade Center. Rita Kempley of ''[[The Washington Post]]'' said \"if we erase the towers from our art, we erase {{sic|it|intended=them}} from our memories\".<ref>{{cite news |last=Kempley |first=Rita |title=The unusual suspects |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/liveonline/02/kempley/kempley051002.htm |newspaper=[[The Washington Post]] |date=May 10, 2002|access-date=November 9, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180301164312/http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/liveonline/02/kempley/kempley051002.htm|archive-date=March 1, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> Author [[Donald Langmead]] compared the phenomenon to the 1949 novel ''[[Nineteen Eighty-Four]]'', where historic mentions of events are retroactively \"rectified\".{{sfnp|Langmead|2009|p=355}} Other filmmakers such as [[Michael Bay]], who directed the 1998 film ''[[Armageddon (1998 film)|Armageddon]]'', opposed retroactively removing references to the World Trade Center based on post-9/11 attitudes.<ref name=\"Mashberg 2019\" />\n\n[[Oliver Stone]]'s film ''[[World Trade Center (film)|World Trade Center]]''\u2014the first movie that specifically examined the effects of the attacks on the World Trade Center, as contrasted with the effects elsewhere\u2014was released in 2006.{{sfnp|Langmead|2009|p=355}} Several years after the attacks, works such as \"The City of New York vs. Homer Simpson\" were placed back in syndication. The [[National September 11 Museum]] has preserved many of the works that feature depictions of the original World Trade Center.<ref name=\"Mashberg 2019\" />\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of tallest buildings in New York City]]\n* [[Artwork damaged or destroyed in the September 11 attacks]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n{{refbegin|colwidth=30em}}\n* {{Cudahy-Hudson}}\n* {{Cite book |last=Darton |first=Eric |title=Divided we stand : a biography of New York's World Trade Center |publisher=[[Basic Books]] | location=New York |year=1999 |isbn=978-0-465-01727-0 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last=Dixon |first=W.W. |title=Film and Television After 9/11 |publisher=[[Southern Illinois University Press]] |year=2004 |isbn=978-0-8093-2556-6 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=fglL9l5knt8C |ref=harv}}\n* {{Cite book |last=Gillespie |first=Angus K. |title=Twin Towers: The Life of New York City's World Trade Center |publisher=[[Rutgers University Press]] |year=1999 |isbn=978-0-8135-2742-0 |url=https://archive.org/details/twintowerslifeof00gill |url-access=registration |ref=harv}}\n* {{Cite book |last1=Glanz |first=James |first2=Eric |last2=Lipton |lastauthoramp=yes |title=City in the Sky |publisher=[[Times Books]] |year=2003 |isbn=978-0-8050-7691-2 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book | last=Goldberger | first=Paul | title=Up from Zero: Politics, Architecture, and the Rebuilding of New York | publisher=Random House Publishing Group | year=2004 | isbn=978-1-58836-422-7 | url=https://archive.org/details/upfromzeropoliti00gold | url-access=registration | ref=harv }}\n* {{cite book |last=Langmead |first=Donald |title=Icons of American Architecture: From the Alamo to the World Trade Center |publisher=[[Greenwood Publishing Group|Greenwood]] |series=Greenwood icons |year=2009 |isbn=978-0-313-34207-3 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=OTh8b2cyGBcC&pg=PA553 | access-date=March 1, 2018 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite web |publisher=Federal Emergency Management Agency |date=May 2002 |title=World Trade Center Building Performance Study |url=https://www.fema.gov/media-library/assets/documents/3544 |access-date=August 21, 2019 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110430200952/http://www.fema.gov/rebuild/mat/wtcstudy.shtm |archivedate=April 30, 2011|ref={{harvid|World Trade Center Building Performance Study|2002}}}}\n* {{Cite book |title=Design and Construction of Structural Systems |publisher=