{"title_page": "Fler", "text_new": "{{Multiple issues|\n{{BLP sources|date=April 2014}}\n{{BLP primary sources|date=April 2014}}\n}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2018}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| image = Fler 2011 by NicoJenner.J\n| caption = Fler in Magdeburg on 20 September 2011\n| image_size = \n| background = solo_singer\n| birth_name = Patrick Losensk\u00fd\n| alias = Frank Nazi White\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1982|4|3}}\n| birth_place = Berlin, Germany\n| origin =\n| genre = [[Drill music|Drill]]\n| years_active = 1999-present\n| label = {{unbulleted list\n|[[Aggro Berlin]] (2003\u20132009)\n|[[Maskulin]] (2011\u2013present)\n}}\n| associated_acts = [[Bushido (rapper)|Bushido]], [[Kay One (rapper)|Kay One]], [[Sido (rapper)|Sido]], [[B-Tight]], [[Silla (rapper)|Silla]], [[French Montana]], [[JayFrance]], [[Juelz Santana]]\n}}\n\n'''Patrick Losensk\u00fd''' (born 3 April 1982), known professionally as '''Fler''', is a [[Germany|German]] [[rapper]] and CEO of Maskulin Music Group.{{citation needed lead|date=November 2018}}\n\n== Career ==\n===2000\u20132005: Beginnings===\nFler was first recognized in the rap scene through collaborations with [[Bushido (rapper)|Bushido]]. Together, they released the collaborative album ''[[Carlo, Cokxxx, Nutten]]'' in October 2002. Fler had five feature parts on Bushido's first studio album, ''[[Vom Bordstein bis zur Skyline]]'', released July 2003.\n\nFler released his first solo album, ''[[Neue Deutsche Welle (album)|Neue Deutsche Welle]]'', on 1 May 2005. The first single was \"NDW 2005\", with a sample of [[Falco (musician)|Falco]]'s \"[[Rock Me Amadeus]]\".<ref>[[Michael Custodis]], ''Tadel verpflichtet. Indizierung von Musik und ihre Wirkung'', in: No Time for Losers. Charts, Listen und andere Kanonisierungen in der Popul\u00e4ren Musik (ASPM Beitr\u00e4ge zur Popularmusikforschung 36), hg. von Dietrich Helms und [[Thomas Phleps]], transcript Bielefeld 2008, {{ISBN|978-3-89942-983-1}}</ref> The album was considered controversial{{according to whom|date=November 2018}} due to perceived right-wing extremist lyrics.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.spiegel.de/kultur/musik/skandal-rap-fler-und-er-a-356560.html |title=Skandal-Rap: Fler und er |date=23 May 2005 |first=Kim |last=Uh-Young |work=[[Spiegel Online]] |language=de |accessdate=28 November 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn 2010, he released a second solo album entitled ''[[Trendsetter (album)|Trendsetter]]''. The first single \"Papa ist zur\u00fcck\" reached {{abbr|No.|number}}&nbsp;23 in Germany and No.&nbsp;32 in Austria. The second single \"C\u00fcs Junge\" was less successful; it reached No.&nbsp;50 in Germany and No.&nbsp;2000 in Austria.\n\n===2008\u20132010: Growth===\nOn 25 January 2008, Fler released his third solo album, ''[[Fremd im eigenen Land (Fler album)|Fremd im eigenen Land]]''. The choice of the title was controversial due to a 1993 song of the same name by [[Advanced Chemistry]].<ref>{{cite book|author1=Florence Feiereisen|author2=Alexandra Merley Hill|title=Germany in the Loud Twentieth Century: An Introduction|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=-T22vJHaIKIC&pg=PA166|year=2012|publisher=Oxford University Press, USA|isbn=978-0-19-975939-2|pages=166\u2013}}</ref>{{elucidate|date=November 2018}} There was also a 2007 album, ''[[Airmax Muzik]]''.{{citation needed|date=November 2018}}\n\nFler had been in a quarrel with Bushido. After the [[Aggro Berlin]] recording label closed, he contacted Bushido and they officially showed their reconciliation with a photo shoot and interview for ''Bravo HipHop Special''.<ref>Bravo HipHop Special, July 2009</ref>\nThey created another collaborative album, ''[[Carlo, Cokxxx, Nutten 2 (2009 album)|Carlo, Cokxxx, Nutten&nbsp;2]]''. Its only single, \"[[Eine Chance/Zu Gangsta]]\", was released on 28&nbsp;August 2009 and reached No.&nbsp;26 in Germany and Austria.\nThe album was released on 11&nbsp;September and reached No.&nbsp;3 in the [[Media Control Charts]].<ref name=\"carlocokxxxnutten.de\">{{cite web|url=http://www.carlocokxxxnutten.de/ |title=carlocokxxxnutten.de |publisher=carlocokxxxnutten.de |date= |accessdate=28 November 2015}}</ref> Bushido stated on the album's website that he \"never believed\" it would have such success considering the lack of promotion or digital release.<ref name=\"carlocokxxxnutten.de\"/>\n\nFler's fifth album, ''[[Flersguterjunge]]'', was released in June 2010 over [[ersguterjunge]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.discogs.com/es/Fler-flersguterjunge/master/792054|title=Fler \u2013 flersguterjunge|website=Discogs}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.last.fm/music/Fler/Flersguterjunge|title=Fler - Flersguterjunge|website=last.fm}}</ref>\n\n===2011\u20132013: Maskulin label===\nOn 11 February 2011, the song \"Nie an mich geglaubt\" from Fler's sixth album, ''[[Airmax Muzik II]]'', was leaked on the Internet as digital single with two remixes, an instrumental version and video shot in New York City. The single entered the German charts at No.&nbsp;64.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.musicline.de/de/chartverfolgung_summary/title/Fler/Nie+An+Mich+Geglaubt/single |title=Die ganze Musik im Internet: Charts |publisher=musicline.de |date= |accessdate=28 November 2015}}</ref> The album was released on 8&nbsp;April through Fler's record label, Maskulin, and reached No.&nbsp;6 on the charts on the 17th calendar week of 2011 (25 April \u2013 1 May).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.musicline.de/de/chartverfolgung_summary/title/Fler/Airmax+Muzik+2+%28premium+Edition%29/longplay |title=Die ganze Musik im Internet: Charts |publisher=musicline.de |date=25 April 2011 |accessdate=28 November 2015}}</ref>\nThe premium edition featured two bonus songs and a 30-minute DVD about the rapper's childhood, with private photos and home movies, and interviews with his stepfather, Shizoe, [[Silla (rapper)|Silla]] and others.<ref>[http://de.paperblog.com/airmax-muzik-2-fler-review-137480/] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110416081437/http://de.paperblog.com/airmax-muzik-2-fler-review-137480/ |date=16 April 2011 }}</ref>\n\nFler's eighth solo album, ''Hinter blauen Augen'', was released on 2&nbsp;November 2012 and reached No.&nbsp;3 in Germany. Music videos were made for the songs \"Nummer&nbsp;1\", \"Hinter blauen Augen\", \"La Vida Loca\" and \"Du bist es wert\". The single \"Nummer&nbsp;1\" reached No.&nbsp;92 on the German charts.\nOn 8&nbsp;February 2013, the single \"Barack Osama\" appeared five days before the music video on YouTube.<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=https://www.amazon.de/Barack-Osama-Fler/dp/B00B23Z0ZY |title=Barack Osama: Amazon.de: Musik |publisher=Amazon.de |date= |accessdate=28 November 2015}}</ref>\nAn instrumental single and a remix version with the rappers Silla and G-Hot was also available. The single rose to No.&nbsp;68 on the German charts.\nOn 19&nbsp;April 2013, the album ''[[Blaues Blut]]'' was released on Maskulin, and reached No.&nbsp;3 on the German charts.<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://www.rap.de/news/news/13173-charts-fler-mit-qblaues-blutq-in-der-top- |title=Charts: Fler mit \"Blaues Blut\" erneut Top 3 |publisher=rap.de |date= |accessdate=28 November 2015}}</ref>\n\n== Artistry ==\n\n===Influences===\nFler has cited several American rappers as his influences including [[Mobb Deep]], [[50 Cent]], [[Lunatic]] and [[Juelz Santana]].\n\n== Business ventures ==\nIn March 2010, Fler opened his clothing store Psalm&nbsp;23, in Berlin-Wilmersdorf. The shop was later renamed Flerstore. In December 2011, the brick-and-mortar store was closed in favor of online sales for clothing and merchandise.{{citation needed|date=April 2014}}<ref>{{cite web |url=http://blog.hiphop.de/FrankWhiteNr.1/65633/ |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2011-07-15 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20120707035919/http://blog.hiphop.de/FrankWhiteNr.1/65633/ |archivedate=2012-07-07 }}</ref>{{unreliable source?|date=April 2014}} Since 2013, he has also established his own line of collections for his fashion brand, Maskulin.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.maskulin.de |title=Maskulin &#124; Der Streetwear Shop |publisher=Maskulin.de |date= |accessdate=28 November 2015}}</ref>\n\n== Attack on Fler ==\nOn 27 September 2007 at 18:00, after co-hosting ''[[MTV]] [[Total Request Live|TRL]]: Urban show'', Fler was attacked by three unknown men armed with knives. One of his bodyguards was able to hold them off, while Fler left through the rear entrance. Nobody was harmed.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.de/article/843374-aggro-berlin-fler-nach-angriff-bei-mtv-unverletzt.html |title=Top News - MTV |publisher=Mtv.de |date= |accessdate=2015-11-28}}</ref>\n\n== Feuds ==\n\n===Eko Fresh===\nIn 2004, [[Eko Fresh]] released the [[Diss (music)|diss track]] \"Die Abrechnung\" ({{lang-en|The Reckoning}}), that mainly attacks [[Kool Savas]], but also referred to various German rappers, including [[Bushido (rapper)|Bushido]], [[Sido (rapper)|Sido]] and Fler.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.laut.de/Eko-Fresh |title=Eko Fresh \u2013 laut.de \u2013 Band |publisher=Laut.de |date= |accessdate=28 November 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2004, Fler responded with \"Hollywoodt\u00fcrke\" ({{lang-en|Hollywood Turk}}), which mocked Eko Fresh as a \"wanna be gangster\" and also references the label [[Royal Bunker]] and rapper [[Bushido (rapper)|Bushido]].\n\nBig Derill, Marcus Staiger and Boba Fettt of Royal Bunker responded with \"Wer? Fler?\" ({{lang-en|Fler who?}})<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.royalbunker.de/audio/ |title=ROYALBUNKER /audio |publisher=Royalbunker.de |date= |accessdate=28 November 2015}}</ref> and Eko Fresh with \"FLERr\u00e4ter\" (a wordplay on ''verr\u00e4ter'', meaning \"traitor\"), a track from his mixtape ''Fick noch immer deine Story'', that also features Bushido.<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://www.hiphop.de/magazin/news/detail/2005/01/10/bushido-und-eko-flerraeter/ |title=Bushido und Eko: Flerr\u00e4ter |publisher=Hiphop.de |date= |accessdate=28 November 2015}}</ref>\nThe feud continued as Fler and [[B-Tight]] dissed Eko Fresh on the track \"Du Opfer\" ({{lang-en|You loser}}).\n\nEko Fresh released a diss track titled \"F.L.E.R.\" in 2006, rapping over the beat of his single \"L.O.V.E.\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=M6zGcJrTusw |title=EGJ Eko Fresh - Diss gegen Fler F.L.E.R |publisher=YouTube |date=2008-04-20 |accessdate=28 November 2015}}</ref> Fler responded on his 2007 mixtape ''[[Airmax Muzik]]'', mentioning Eko Fresh on some tracks. After that, both rappers kept quiet for some time. In 2011, Fler name-dropped Eko Fresh in his song \"Autopsie\", featured on the mixtape ''[[Airmax Muzik II]]''. Following that, Eko Fresh [[tweeted]] with irony to his fans, to buy Fler's album and called the song \"whack\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://hiphopholic.de/eko-fresh-macht-sich-uber-fler-lustig-bitte-kauft-euch-alle-airmax-muzik-ein-gutes-stuck-imagerap/ |title=Eko Fresh macht sich \u00fcber Fler lustig: \"Bitte kauft euch alle Airmax Muzik, ein gutes St\u00fcck Imagerap\" |publisher=hiphopholic.de |date= |accessdate=28 November 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Kollegah===\nOn 11 March 2009, the artists of label [[Selfmade Records]] released ''Chronik 2''. It features the track \"Westdeutschlands Kings\" by [[Kollegah]], [[Favorite (rapper)|Favorite]] and [[Farid Bang]], a diss track aimed at [[Sido (rapper)|Sido]], Fler and [[Kitty Kat]].<ref>[http://www.bassdraft.com/de/news/Aggro_Diss_Westdeutschlands_Kings/index.html] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110707213450/http://www.bassdraft.com/de/news/Aggro_Diss_Westdeutschlands_Kings/index.html |date=7 July 2011 }}</ref>\n\nOn 20 March, Kollegah released \"Fanpost\", where he insulted Fler calling him a \"fat potato\" and mocked him claiming that he was penetrated with a carrot.<ref>[http://www.bassdraft.com/de/news/Kollegah_Fanpost_Fler_Diss/] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110707213801/http://www.bassdraft.com/de/news/Kollegah_Fanpost_Fler_Diss/ |date=7 July 2011 }}</ref>\nFler responded with the song titled \"Schrei nach Liebe\" ({{lang-en|Scream for love}}), which was based on [[Schrei nach Liebe|the song of the same name]] by [[Die \u00c4rzte]].<ref>[http://www.bassdraft.com/de/news/Fler_Schrei_nach_Liebe_Kollegah_Diss/index.html] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110707213812/http://www.bassdraft.com/de/news/Fler_Schrei_nach_Liebe_Kollegah_Diss/index.html |date=7 July 2011 }}</ref> After that, both rappers were quiet for nearly a year. In 2011, Fler name-dropped Kollegah in his song \"Autopsie\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.laut.de/Fler/Air-Max-Muzik-II-(Album) |title=\"Air Max Muzik II\" von Fler \u2013 laut.de \u2013 Album |publisher=Laut.de |date= |accessdate=28 November 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn 2013, after the release of Kollegah and Farid Bang's collaboration album ''[[Jung, brutal, gutaussehend 2]]'', Fler released a track called \"Mut zur H\u00e4sslichkeit\" ({{lang-en|Courage to ugliness}}), in which he made fun of their image and also imitates them.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://meinrap.de/2013/02/27/fler-mut-zur-hasslichkeit-jbg-audio/ |title=Fler - Mut zur H\u00e4sslichkeit (JBG) (Audio) |publisher=MeinRap.de |date= |accessdate=28 November 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130228210340/http://meinrap.de/2013/02/27/fler-mut-zur-hasslichkeit-jbg-audio/ |archive-date=28 February 2013 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n{{Main article|Fler discography}}\n{{Col-begin}}\n{{Col-2}}\n\n===Studio albums===\n* 2005: ''[[Neue Deutsche Welle (album)|Neue Deutsche Welle]]''\n* 2006: ''[[Trendsetter (album)|Trendsetter]]''\n* 2008: ''[[Fremd im eigenen Land (Fler album)|Fremd im eignen Land]]''\n* 2009: ''[[Fler (album)|Fler]]''\n* 2010: ''[[Flersguterjunge]]''\n* 2011: ''[[Airmax Muzik II]]''\n* 2011: ''Im Bus ganz hinten''\n* 2012: ''Hinter blauen Augen''\n* 2013: ''[[Blaues Blut]]''\n* 2014: ''Neue Deutsche Welle 2''\n* 2015: ''Keiner kommt klar mit mir''\n{{Col-2}}\n* 2015: ''[[Weil Die Stra\u00dfe Nicht Vergisst]]''\n* 2016: ''Vibe''\n* 2018: ''Flizzy''\n* 2019: ''Colucci''\n* 2020: ''Atlantis''\n\n===Collaboration===\n*2002: ''[[Carlo Cokxxx Nutten]]'' <small>(with [[Bushido (rapper)|Bushido]])</small>\n*2008: ''[[S\u00fcdberlin Maskulin]]'' <small>(with [[Godsilla]])</small>\n*2009: ''[[Carlo Cokxxx Nutten 2]]'' <small>(with Bushido)</small>\n*2010: ''[[Berlins Most Wanted (Album)|Berlins Most Wanted]]'' <small>(with [[Berlins Most Wanted]])</small>\n*2012: ''S\u00fcdberlin Maskulin II'' <small>(with [[Silla (rapper)|Silla]])</small>\n*2017: ''Epic'' <small>(with [[Jalil (rapper)|Jalil]])</small>\n{{col-end}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Official website|http://www.fler.de/}}\n\n{{Fler}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:1982 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:German rappers]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Berlin]]\n[[Category:German people of Czech descent]]\n", "text_old": "{{Multiple issues|\n{{BLP sources|date=April 2014}}\n{{BLP primary sources|date=April 2014}}\n}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2018}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| image = Fler 2011 by NicoJenner.JPG\n| caption = Fler in Magdeburg on 20 September 2011\n| image_size = \n| background = solo_singer\n| birth_name = Patrick Losensk\u00fd\n| alias = Frank White\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1982|4|3}}\n| birth_place = Berlin, Germany\n| origin =\n| genre = [[Drill music|Drill]]\n| years_active = 1999-present\n| label = {{unbulleted list\n|[[Aggro Berlin]] (2003\u20132009)\n|[[Maskulin]] (2011\u2013present)\n}}\n| associated_acts = [[Bushido (rapper)|Bushido]], [[Kay One (rapper)|Kay One]], [[Sido (rapper)|Sido]], [[B-Tight]], [[Silla (rapper)|Silla]], [[French Montana]], [[JayFrance]], [[Juelz Santana]]\n}}\n\n'''Patrick Losensk\u00fd''' (born 3 April 1982), known professionally as '''Fler''', is a [[Germany|German]] [[rapper]] and CEO of Maskulin Music Group.{{citation needed lead|date=November 2018}}\n\n== Career ==\n===2000\u20132005: Beginnings===\nFler was first recognized in the rap scene through collaborations with [[Bushido (rapper)|Bushido]]. Together, they released the collaborative album ''[[Carlo, Cokxxx, Nutten]]'' in October 2002. Fler had five feature parts on Bushido's first studio album, ''[[Vom Bordstein bis zur Skyline]]'', released July 2003.\n\nFler released his first solo album, ''[[Neue Deutsche Welle (album)|Neue Deutsche Welle]]'', on 1 May 2005. The first single was \"NDW 2005\", with a sample of [[Falco (musician)|Falco]]'s \"[[Rock Me Amadeus]]\".<ref>[[Michael Custodis]], ''Tadel verpflichtet. Indizierung von Musik und ihre Wirkung'', in: No Time for Losers. Charts, Listen und andere Kanonisierungen in der Popul\u00e4ren Musik (ASPM Beitr\u00e4ge zur Popularmusikforschung 36), hg. von Dietrich Helms und [[Thomas Phleps]], transcript Bielefeld 2008, {{ISBN|978-3-89942-983-1}}</ref> The album was considered controversial{{according to whom|date=November 2018}} due to perceived right-wing extremist lyrics.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.spiegel.de/kultur/musik/skandal-rap-fler-und-er-a-356560.html |title=Skandal-Rap: Fler und er |date=23 May 2005 |first=Kim |last=Uh-Young |work=[[Spiegel Online]] |language=de |accessdate=28 November 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn 2010, he released a second solo album entitled ''[[Trendsetter (album)|Trendsetter]]''. The first single \"Papa ist zur\u00fcck\" reached {{abbr|No.|number}}&nbsp;23 in Germany and No.&nbsp;32 in Austria. The second single \"C\u00fcs Junge\" was less successful; it reached No.&nbsp;50 in Germany and No.&nbsp;2000 in Austria.\n\n===2008\u20132010: Growth===\nOn 25 January 2008, Fler released his third solo album, ''[[Fremd im eigenen Land (Fler album)|Fremd im eigenen Land]]''. The choice of the title was controversial due to a 1993 song of the same name by [[Advanced Chemistry]].<ref>{{cite book|author1=Florence Feiereisen|author2=Alexandra Merley Hill|title=Germany in the Loud Twentieth Century: An Introduction|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=-T22vJHaIKIC&pg=PA166|year=2012|publisher=Oxford University Press, USA|isbn=978-0-19-975939-2|pages=166\u2013}}</ref>{{elucidate|date=November 2018}} There was also a 2007 album, ''[[Airmax Muzik]]''.{{citation needed|date=November 2018}}\n\nFler had been in a quarrel with Bushido. After the [[Aggro Berlin]] recording label closed, he contacted Bushido and they officially showed their reconciliation with a photo shoot and interview for ''Bravo HipHop Special''.<ref>Bravo HipHop Special, July 2009</ref>\nThey created another collaborative album, ''[[Carlo, Cokxxx, Nutten 2 (2009 album)|Carlo, Cokxxx, Nutten&nbsp;2]]''. Its only single, \"[[Eine Chance/Zu Gangsta]]\", was released on 28&nbsp;August 2009 and reached No.&nbsp;26 in Germany and Austria.\nThe album was released on 11&nbsp;September and reached No.&nbsp;3 in the [[Media Control Charts]].<ref name=\"carlocokxxxnutten.de\">{{cite web|url=http://www.carlocokxxxnutten.de/ |title=carlocokxxxnutten.de |publisher=carlocokxxxnutten.de |date= |accessdate=28 November 2015}}</ref> Bushido stated on the album's website that he \"never believed\" it would have such success considering the lack of promotion or digital release.<ref name=\"carlocokxxxnutten.de\"/>\n\nFler's fifth album, ''[[Flersguterjunge]]'', was released in June 2010 over [[ersguterjunge]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.discogs.com/es/Fler-flersguterjunge/master/792054|title=Fler \u2013 flersguterjunge|website=Discogs}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.last.fm/music/Fler/Flersguterjunge|title=Fler - Flersguterjunge|website=last.fm}}</ref>\n\n===2011\u20132013: Maskulin label===\nOn 11 February 2011, the song \"Nie an mich geglaubt\" from Fler's sixth album, ''[[Airmax Muzik II]]'', was leaked on the Internet as digital single with two remixes, an instrumental version and video shot in New York City. The single entered the German charts at No.&nbsp;64.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.musicline.de/de/chartverfolgung_summary/title/Fler/Nie+An+Mich+Geglaubt/single |title=Die ganze Musik im Internet: Charts |publisher=musicline.de |date= |accessdate=28 November 2015}}</ref> The album was released on 8&nbsp;April through Fler's record label, Maskulin, and reached No.&nbsp;6 on the charts on the 17th calendar week of 2011 (25 April \u2013 1 May).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.musicline.de/de/chartverfolgung_summary/title/Fler/Airmax+Muzik+2+%28premium+Edition%29/longplay |title=Die ganze Musik im Internet: Charts |publisher=musicline.de |date=25 April 2011 |accessdate=28 November 2015}}</ref>\nThe premium edition featured two bonus songs and a 30-minute DVD about the rapper's childhood, with private photos and home movies, and interviews with his stepfather, Shizoe, [[Silla (rapper)|Silla]] and others.<ref>[http://de.paperblog.com/airmax-muzik-2-fler-review-137480/] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110416081437/http://de.paperblog.com/airmax-muzik-2-fler-review-137480/ |date=16 April 2011 }}</ref>\n\nFler's eighth solo album, ''Hinter blauen Augen'', was released on 2&nbsp;November 2012 and reached No.&nbsp;3 in Germany. Music videos were made for the songs \"Nummer&nbsp;1\", \"Hinter blauen Augen\", \"La Vida Loca\" and \"Du bist es wert\". The single \"Nummer&nbsp;1\" reached No.&nbsp;92 on the German charts.\nOn 8&nbsp;February 2013, the single \"Barack Osama\" appeared five days before the music video on YouTube.<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=https://www.amazon.de/Barack-Osama-Fler/dp/B00B23Z0ZY |title=Barack Osama: Amazon.de: Musik |publisher=Amazon.de |date= |accessdate=28 November 2015}}</ref>\nAn instrumental single and a remix version with the rappers Silla and G-Hot was also available. The single rose to No.&nbsp;68 on the German charts.\nOn 19&nbsp;April 2013, the album ''[[Blaues Blut]]'' was released on Maskulin, and reached No.&nbsp;3 on the German charts.<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://www.rap.de/news/news/13173-charts-fler-mit-qblaues-blutq-in-der-top- |title=Charts: Fler mit \"Blaues Blut\" erneut Top 3 |publisher=rap.de |date= |accessdate=28 November 2015}}</ref>\n\n== Artistry ==\n\n===Influences===\nFler has cited several American rappers as his influences including [[Mobb Deep]], [[50 Cent]], [[Lunatic]] and [[Juelz Santana]].\n\n== Business ventures ==\nIn March 2010, Fler opened his clothing store Psalm&nbsp;23, in Berlin-Wilmersdorf. The shop was later renamed Flerstore. In December 2011, the brick-and-mortar store was closed in favor of online sales for clothing and merchandise.{{citation needed|date=April 2014}}<ref>{{cite web |url=http://blog.hiphop.de/FrankWhiteNr.1/65633/ |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2011-07-15 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20120707035919/http://blog.hiphop.de/FrankWhiteNr.1/65633/ |archivedate=2012-07-07 }}</ref>{{unreliable source?|date=April 2014}} Since 2013, he has also established his own line of collections for his fashion brand, Maskulin.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.maskulin.de |title=Maskulin &#124; Der Streetwear Shop |publisher=Maskulin.de |date= |accessdate=28 November 2015}}</ref>\n\n== Attack on Fler ==\nOn 27 September 2007 at 18:00, after co-hosting ''[[MTV]] [[Total Request Live|TRL]]: Urban show'', Fler was attacked by three unknown men armed with knives. One of his bodyguards was able to hold them off, while Fler left through the rear entrance. Nobody was harmed.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.de/article/843374-aggro-berlin-fler-nach-angriff-bei-mtv-unverletzt.html |title=Top News - MTV |publisher=Mtv.de |date= |accessdate=2015-11-28}}</ref>\n\n== Feuds ==\n\n===Eko Fresh===\nIn 2004, [[Eko Fresh]] released the [[Diss (music)|diss track]] \"Die Abrechnung\" ({{lang-en|The Reckoning}}), that mainly attacks [[Kool Savas]], but also referred to various German rappers, including [[Bushido (rapper)|Bushido]], [[Sido (rapper)|Sido]] and Fler.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.laut.de/Eko-Fresh |title=Eko Fresh \u2013 laut.de \u2013 Band |publisher=Laut.de |date= |accessdate=28 November 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2004, Fler responded with \"Hollywoodt\u00fcrke\" ({{lang-en|Hollywood Turk}}), which mocked Eko Fresh as a \"wanna be gangster\" and also references the label [[Royal Bunker]] and rapper [[Bushido (rapper)|Bushido]].\n\nBig Derill, Marcus Staiger and Boba Fettt of Royal Bunker responded with \"Wer? Fler?\" ({{lang-en|Fler who?}})<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.royalbunker.de/audio/ |title=ROYALBUNKER /audio |publisher=Royalbunker.de |date= |accessdate=28 November 2015}}</ref> and Eko Fresh with \"FLERr\u00e4ter\" (a wordplay on ''verr\u00e4ter'', meaning \"traitor\"), a track from his mixtape ''Fick noch immer deine Story'', that also features Bushido.<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://www.hiphop.de/magazin/news/detail/2005/01/10/bushido-und-eko-flerraeter/ |title=Bushido und Eko: Flerr\u00e4ter |publisher=Hiphop.de |date= |accessdate=28 November 2015}}</ref>\nThe feud continued as Fler and [[B-Tight]] dissed Eko Fresh on the track \"Du Opfer\" ({{lang-en|You loser}}).\n\nEko Fresh released a diss track titled \"F.L.E.R.\" in 2006, rapping over the beat of his single \"L.O.V.E.\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=M6zGcJrTusw |title=EGJ Eko Fresh - Diss gegen Fler F.L.E.R |publisher=YouTube |date=2008-04-20 |accessdate=28 November 2015}}</ref> Fler responded on his 2007 mixtape ''[[Airmax Muzik]]'', mentioning Eko Fresh on some tracks. After that, both rappers kept quiet for some time. In 2011, Fler name-dropped Eko Fresh in his song \"Autopsie\", featured on the mixtape ''[[Airmax Muzik II]]''. Following that, Eko Fresh [[tweeted]] with irony to his fans, to buy Fler's album and called the song \"whack\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://hiphopholic.de/eko-fresh-macht-sich-uber-fler-lustig-bitte-kauft-euch-alle-airmax-muzik-ein-gutes-stuck-imagerap/ |title=Eko Fresh macht sich \u00fcber Fler lustig: \"Bitte kauft euch alle Airmax Muzik, ein gutes St\u00fcck Imagerap\" |publisher=hiphopholic.de |date= |accessdate=28 November 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Kollegah===\nOn 11 March 2009, the artists of label [[Selfmade Records]] released ''Chronik 2''. It features the track \"Westdeutschlands Kings\" by [[Kollegah]], [[Favorite (rapper)|Favorite]] and [[Farid Bang]], a diss track aimed at [[Sido (rapper)|Sido]], Fler and [[Kitty Kat]].<ref>[http://www.bassdraft.com/de/news/Aggro_Diss_Westdeutschlands_Kings/index.html] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110707213450/http://www.bassdraft.com/de/news/Aggro_Diss_Westdeutschlands_Kings/index.html |date=7 July 2011 }}</ref>\n\nOn 20 March, Kollegah released \"Fanpost\", where he insulted Fler calling him a \"fat potato\" and mocked him claiming that he was penetrated with a carrot.<ref>[http://www.bassdraft.com/de/news/Kollegah_Fanpost_Fler_Diss/] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110707213801/http://www.bassdraft.com/de/news/Kollegah_Fanpost_Fler_Diss/ |date=7 July 2011 }}</ref>\nFler responded with the song titled \"Schrei nach Liebe\" ({{lang-en|Scream for love}}), which was based on [[Schrei nach Liebe|the song of the same name]] by [[Die \u00c4rzte]].<ref>[http://www.bassdraft.com/de/news/Fler_Schrei_nach_Liebe_Kollegah_Diss/index.html] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110707213812/http://www.bassdraft.com/de/news/Fler_Schrei_nach_Liebe_Kollegah_Diss/index.html |date=7 July 2011 }}</ref> After that, both rappers were quiet for nearly a year. In 2011, Fler name-dropped Kollegah in his song \"Autopsie\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.laut.de/Fler/Air-Max-Muzik-II-(Album) |title=\"Air Max Muzik II\" von Fler \u2013 laut.de \u2013 Album |publisher=Laut.de |date= |accessdate=28 November 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn 2013, after the release of Kollegah and Farid Bang's collaboration album ''[[Jung, brutal, gutaussehend 2]]'', Fler released a track called \"Mut zur H\u00e4sslichkeit\" ({{lang-en|Courage to ugliness}}), in which he made fun of their image and also imitates them.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://meinrap.de/2013/02/27/fler-mut-zur-hasslichkeit-jbg-audio/ |title=Fler - Mut zur H\u00e4sslichkeit (JBG) (Audio) |publisher=MeinRap.de |date= |accessdate=28 November 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130228210340/http://meinrap.de/2013/02/27/fler-mut-zur-hasslichkeit-jbg-audio/ |archive-date=28 February 2013 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n{{Main article|Fler discography}}\n{{Col-begin}}\n{{Col-2}}\n\n===Studio albums===\n* 2005: ''[[Neue Deutsche Welle (album)|Neue Deutsche Welle]]''\n* 2006: ''[[Trendsetter (album)|Trendsetter]]''\n* 2008: ''[[Fremd im eigenen Land (Fler album)|Fremd im eignen Land]]''\n* 2009: ''[[Fler (album)|Fler]]''\n* 2010: ''[[Flersguterjunge]]''\n* 2011: ''[[Airmax Muzik II]]''\n* 2011: ''Im Bus ganz hinten''\n* 2012: ''Hinter blauen Augen''\n* 2013: ''[[Blaues Blut]]''\n* 2014: ''Neue Deutsche Welle 2''\n* 2015: ''Keiner kommt klar mit mir''\n{{Col-2}}\n* 2015: ''[[Weil Die Stra\u00dfe Nicht Vergisst]]''\n* 2016: ''Vibe''\n* 2018: ''Flizzy''\n* 2019: ''Colucci''\n* 2020: ''Atlantis''\n\n===Collaboration===\n*2002: ''[[Carlo Cokxxx Nutten]]'' <small>(with [[Bushido (rapper)|Bushido]])</small>\n*2008: ''[[S\u00fcdberlin Maskulin]]'' <small>(with [[Godsilla]])</small>\n*2009: ''[[Carlo Cokxxx Nutten 2]]'' <small>(with Bushido)</small>\n*2010: ''[[Berlins Most Wanted (Album)|Berlins Most Wanted]]'' <small>(with [[Berlins Most Wanted]])</small>\n*2012: ''S\u00fcdberlin Maskulin II'' <small>(with [[Silla (rapper)|Silla]])</small>\n*2017: ''Epic'' <small>(with [[Jalil (rapper)|Jalil]])</small>\n{{col-end}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Official website|http://www.fler.de/}}\n\n{{Fler}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:1982 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:German rappers]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Berlin]]\n[[Category:German people of Czech descent]]\n", "name_user": "31.17.110.176", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(To fix it he is a german Nazi)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fler"}
{"title_page": "Shillelagh (club)", "text_new": "{{For|other things called \"shillelagh\"|Shillelagh (disambiguation)}}\n{{EngvarB|date=February 2018}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2018}}\n[[File:Assorted shillelagh.JPG|thumb|right|Assorted shillelaghs.]]\nA '''shillelagh''' ({{IPAc-en|\u0283|\u1d7b|\u02c8|l|e\u026a|l|i}} {{respell|shi|LAY|lee}} or {{IPAc-en|\u0283|\u1d7b|\u02c8|l|e\u026a|l|\u0259}} {{respell|shi|LAY|l\u0259}}; {{lang-ga|sail \u00e9ille}} or {{lang|ga|saill \u00e9alaigh}}<ref name=barry/> {{IPA-ga|\u02c8sal\u02b2 \u02c8e\u02d0l\u0320\u02b2\u0259|}}, \"thonged willow\") is a wooden walking stick and [[Club (weapon)|club or cudgel]], typically made from a stout knotty [[blackthorn]] stick with a large knob at the top.  It is associated with Ireland and [[Irish mythology|Irish folklore]].\n\nOther spelling variants include '''shillelah''', '''shillalah''', and '''shillaly'''.\n\n== Etymology ==\nThe name shillelagh is the [[Hiberno-English]] [[Corruption (linguistics)|corruption]] of the Irish (Gaelic) form {{lang|ga|sail \u00e9ille}}, where {{lang|ga|sail}} means \"willow\" or \"cudgel\" and {{lang|ga|\u00e9ille}} is [[genitive]] for {{lang|ga|iall}} meaning \"thong\", \"strap\", \"leash\", \"string\", etc.{{sfnp|Hurley|2007|p=121}}<ref name=dict-dolan/>\n\nAs an alternate etymology, [[Mrs. S. C. Hall]] as well as [[P. W. Joyce]] have written that the name may have derived from the wood being sourced from forest land in the village or [[Barony (Ireland)|barony]] of [[Shillelagh (barony)|Shillelagh, County Wicklow]].  The geographic name Shillelagh derives from {{lang|ga|S\u00edol \u00c9alaigh}}\u3000\"Descendants of \u00c9alach\".<ref name=hall/>{{sfnp|Hurley|2007|p=119}}<ref>[http://www.oed.com/view/Entry/178130?redirectedFrom=shillelagh#eid Oxford English Dictionary]: Etymology: < the name of a barony and village in Co. Wicklow. OED provides the following quotation: \"1785 F. Grose ''Classical Dict. Vulgar Tongue'', ''Shillaley'', an oaken sapling, or cudgel, (Irish) from a wood of that name famous for its oaks.\"</ref><ref>[http://www.etymonline.com/index.php?term=shillelagh Online Etymology Dictionary]: ''shillelagh'' 1772, \"cudgel,\" earlier, \"oak wood used to make cudgels\" (1670s), from ''Shillelagh'', town and barony in Co. Wicklow, Ireland, famous for its oaks.</ref>\n\n== Construction ==\nShillelaghs are traditionally made from [[blackthorn]] (sloe) wood (''Prunus spinosa'') or oak.<ref name=\"chouinard\">{{cite journal |last1=Chouinard B.A. |first1=Maxime |title=The stick is king: The Shillelagh Bata or the rediscovery of a living Irish martial tradition |url=http://www.freifechter.com/files/stick_edited.pdf |accessdate=5 July 2011 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120302040109/http://www.freifechter.com/files/stick_edited.pdf |archivedate=2012-03-02}}; [http://cimande.com/blackthorn/pdf/stick_edited.pdf copy].</ref> With the scarcity of oak in Ireland the term came increasingly to denote a blackthorn stick,{{sfnp|Colum|1988|p=397}} and indeed '''blackthorn stick''' is sometimes glossed as equivalent to shillelagh.<ref name=mchugh/><ref name=mabey/>\n\nWood from the root was prized since this would be used for the knob,<ref name=\"chouinard\"/> and was less prone to crack or break during use.\n\n=== Curing and polishing ===\nMost commonly, the chosen wood would be placed up a chimney to cure for a duration of several months to several years;{{Refn|group=lower-alpha|The stick may be smeared with butter <!--or lard (no ref)--> before being hung in the chimney, as a preparatory step.<ref name=hall/>}} the accumulated layer of [[soot]] gave the shillelagh its typical black shiny appearance.<ref name=hall/><ref name=\"chouinard\"/>\n\nThe less frequent methods were to bury the shank in a dung pile, or even in [[Calcium hydroxide|slack lime]].<ref name=hall/><!--for roughly the same amount of time.--> The stick may require protection from its dung bath by being wrapped in well-greased oiled brown paper (steeped in hog's lard or oil).<ref name=carleton/>\n\nBoth of the previous methods would be finished with oils or sealants, etc. A further coat of special soot finish may be applied,<ref name=\"chouinard\"/> or a mixture of [[Graphite|black lead]] and grease rubbed on with woolen cloth to a polishing finish.<ref name=carleton/> Some examples may just be given a coat of black paint.<ref name=irish-times/>\n\nRarer still was [[brining]], where the shank was placed into a basin of saltwater. The saltwater, being a hypertonic solution, would pull moisture from the shank with little warping.{{cn|date=July 2019}} One isolated case of this brining method being used, by [[Charlotte Bront\u00eb]]'s uncle named Hugh, has been documented. Hugh Bront\u00eb is said to have rubbed train oil ([[whale oil]]) on the stick using [[chamois leather]], and applied [[magpie]] blood to give it a darker appearance.<ref name=wright/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://hemamisfits.com/2014/06/09/shillelaghs/ |last=Chouinard |first=Maxime |title=Shillelaghs |date=9 June 2014}}</ref>\n\n=== Dimensions ===\n[[File:Shillelaghs in various stages of completion.jpg|thumb|Oaken shillelaghs in various stages of completion]]\n\nThey are commonly the length of a walking stick (distance from the floor to one's wrist with elbow slightly bent),{{cn|date=July 2019}} or rather longer, about 4 feet or 5 feet, as opposed to the walking stick measuring about 3 feet.{{sfnp|Hurley|2007|pp=144, 157}} In the broad sense, the Shillealagh ''bata'' or sticks could include short mallets only 1 \u2013 2 feet long to long poles 6 \u2013 9 feet.<ref name=\"chouinard\"/>\n\n=== Fittings ===\nShillelaghs may be hollowed at the heavy \"hitting\" end and filled with molten lead to increase the weight beyond the typical two pounds; this sort of shillelagh is known as a 'loaded stick'.{{Refn|group=\"lower-alpha\"|These loaded versions are called by such names as ''smacht\u00edn''\u3000(''smacht\u00edn ceann luaidhe'' or \"lead-headed cudgel\"), and are the size of smaller ''ailp\u00edn''.{{sfnp|Hurley|2007|p=148}}}}<ref name=\"chouinard\"/>{{sfnp|Hurley|2007|p=148}}\n\nThe loaded types needed to have its knob fitted with iron [[ferrules]] to maintain structural integrity.{{sfnp|Hurley|2007|p=148}} But the sticks also got iron ferrules fitted onto its narrow end as well.<ref name=\"wright\"/>{{sfnp|Hurley|2007|p=145}}<ref name=\"chouinard\"/> Shillelagh may also have a heavy knob for a handle which can be used for striking.{{sfnp|Colum|1988|p=397}}<!--as well as parrying and disarming an opponent. (no book source found; Keelly &Rogers (1999) ''How to be Irish'' suggests the opposite: \"knob end was employed to strike, and the other end to parry\") --> Shillelaghs may also have a strap attached, similar to commercially made walking sticks, to place around the holder's wrist.<ref name=mccann/>\n\n== History ==\n\nThe shillelagh was originally used for settling disputes in a gentlemanly manner \u2014 like a duel with pistols or swords. Modern practitioners of [[bataireacht]] study the use of the shillelagh for self-defense and as a [[martial art]]. Of the practice, researcher J. W. Hurley writes:\n\n<blockquote>\nMethods of shillelagh fighting have evolved over a period of thousands of years, from the spear, staff, axe and sword fighting of the Irish. There is some evidence which suggests that the use of Irish stick weapons may have evolved in a progression from a reliance on long spears and [[wattles]], to shorter spears and wattles, to the shillelagh, alpeen,{{Refn|group=\"lower-alpha\"|There is only a vague distinction between shillelagh and alpeen (Diarmaid \u00d3 Muirithe), though the alpeen may be longer or heavier, and be knobbed in the minds of some ([[P. W. Joyce]]).{{sfnp|Hurley|2007|p=131}} An ''alpeen'' or ''ailpeen'' ({{lang-ga|ailp\u00edn}}) is glossed as. \"thick [[alpenstock]]\", \"[[walking stick#Types|ashplant]]\", \"club\", \"heavy stick\".<ref>{{harvp|Dolan|2006}} \"ailpeen, alpeen\", ''Dictionary of Hiberno-English'', pp. 5\u20136.</ref>}} blackthorn (walking-stick) and short cudgel. By the 19th century Irish shillelagh-fighting had evolved into a practice which involved the use of three basic types of weapons, sticks which were long, medium or short in length.{{sfnp|Hurley|2007|p=347}}</blockquote>\n\n== Folklore and balladry ==\nShillelaghs are sometimes referred to in a similar context in folk songs. In the ballad \"[[Finnegan's Wake]]\" occurs the phrase \"Shillelagh law did all engage\", signifying that a brawl has broken out;<ref name=crowley/> \"shillelagh law\" itself has been explained as meaning the accepted rule governing the usage of the weapon.{{sfnp|Hurley|2007|p=11}}\n\nThe anti-recruiting folk song \"[[Arthur McBride]]\", where the recruiters are struck with a shillelagh,<ref name=bonnie/><ref name=james/> and in the 19th century song \"[[Rocky Road to Dublin]]\", in which references are made to fashioning a shillelagh (\"I cut a stout blackthorn\"), and using it (\"shillalah\"<ref name=carleton-rocky/>) to hold a tied bag over one's shoulder, and using it as a striking weapon.<ref name=bonnie-rocky/>\n\n[[Charles Dibdin the younger]] wrote a song entitled \"The Twig of Shelaly\",<ref name=dibdin-shelaly/> later reprinted as \"The Twig of Shillelah\".<ref name=albion/>\n\n== Modern usage ==\n[[Image:Jeweledshillelagh.jpg|thumb|right|The Jeweled Shillelagh]]\nThe shillelegah came to be regarded as a stereotypical symbol of Irishness in popular culture,{{sfnp|Hurley|2007|p=15}} particularly in an Irish-American context.\n\nMembers of a number of [[Irish_in_the_British_Armed_Forces#Regiments|Irish regiments in the British Armed Forces]] have traditionally carried Blackthorn sticks, including officers of the [[Irish Guards]].<ref name=\"matusitz2014\">{{cite book |title = Symbolism in Terrorism: Motivation, Communication, and Behavior | last = Matusitz |first= Jonathan | publisher = Rowman & Littlefield | year = 2014 | page = 208 | isbn = 9781442235793 | quote = More recently, the MGM-51 antitank missile [..] was baptized as the \"Shillelagh\". Officers of the Irish Guards are given shillelaghs upon graduation - just like Irish Regiments of the British Army in the past }}</ref> Officers of the [[69th Infantry Regiment (New York)|Fighting 69th]] regiment of the United States [[Army National Guard]] also carry shillelaghs as rank badges in parades.<ref>{{cite web | title=Green Camouflage and Purple Hearts | author=Alan Feuer | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2005/03/18/nyregion/18fighting.html| work=[[The New York Times]] | date=18 March 2005 | accessdate=6 October 2008}}</ref> \n\nIn sports, the [[Boston Celtics]] logo has a [[leprechaun]] leaning on his shillelagh, and it also features with the leprechaun on some logos of [[Confraternity of Brothers Clubs|Brothers]] [[Rugby league]] teams in Australia. In San Diego, [[San Diego Padres|Padres]] broadcaster [[Mark Andrew Grant|Mark Grant]] popularised the shillelagh as a rally call, by using terms like \"Shillelagh Power\" to describe late game heroics by the Padres. The success of the phrase led the San Diego Padres store to carry [[inflatable]] shillelaghs. Similarly, in the [[college football|college games of American football]], a [[Jeweled Shillelagh]] is the trophy given to the winner of the [[college rivalry|rivalry game]] between the [[USC Trojans]] and [[Notre Dame Fighting Irish]]. Professional wrestler [[Dave Finlay|Finlay]] carried a shillelagh to the ring in December 2006 as an \"illegal weapon\".{{fact|date=December 2019}}\n\nA number of items take their name from the shillelegah, including the [[MGM-51 Shillelagh]] anti-tank missile,<ref name=\"matusitz2014\"/> and several aircraft of the [[357th Fighter Group]] which were named for the club, and had similar representative nose art.{{fact|date=July 2019}} In the tabletop game [[Dungeons and Dragons]], 'shillelagh' is a low-level spell used by casters to make simple clubs into powerful bludgeoning weapons.<ref>{{cite book | last=Dungeons & Dragons | title=Player's Handbook | url=http://dnd.wizards.com/products/tabletop-games/rpg-products/rpg_playershandbook | edition=5e | publisher=[[Wizards of the Coast]] | year=2014 | isbn=978-0-7869-6560-1 }}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Rungu (weapon)]] - a similar club common in East Africa.\n* [[Knobkierie]] - similar club associated with Southern Africa and [[World War I]] British troops.\n* [[Sgian-dubh]] - \"black knife\" of Scottish Highland attire\n\n== Explanatory notes ==\n{{notelist}}\n\n== References ==\n===Notes===\n{{Reflist|30em|refs=\n<ref name=albion>{{cite book|ref=harv|last=Dibdin|first=C., Jr. |authorlink=Charles Isaac Mungo Dibdin |title=The Twig of Shillelah |work=The Pride of Albion. A Collection of New and Pleasing Songs, Etc |publisher=T. Hughes |year=1810 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=zzVYAAAAcAAJ&pg=PA126 |pages=12\u201387}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=barry>{{cite book|ref=harv|last=Barry |first=Michael |authorlink=<!--Michael Barry (Irish writer)--> |title=Dublin's Strangest Tales: Extraordinary but true stories |publisher=[[Pavilion Books]] |year=2013 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=IrO_CAAAQBAJ&pg=PT9 |page=9|isbn=9781909396449 }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=bonnie>{{cite book|last1=Milner |first1=Dan |authorlink1=Dan Milner |last2=Kaplan  |first2=Paul |authorlink2=<!--Paul Kaplan--> |title=Arthur McBride |work=Songs of England, Ireland, and Scotland: A Bonnie Bunch of Roses  |location=|publisher=Oak Publications |year=1983 |isbn=1-783234-92-X |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ZpbIDgAAQBAJ&pg=PT87 |pages=87\u201388}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=bonnie-rocky>{{cite book|last1=Milner |first1=Dan |authorlink1=Dan Milner |last2=Kaplan  |first2=Paul |authorlink2=<!--Paul Kaplan--> |title=The Rocky Road to Dublin |work=Songs of England, Ireland, and Scotland: A Bonnie Bunch of Roses  |location=|publisher=Oak Publications |year=1983 |isbn=1-783234-92-X |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ZpbIDgAAQBAJ&pg=PT58|pages=58\u201359}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=carleton>{{cite book|ref=harv|last=Carleton |first=William |authorlink=William Carleton |title=Ireland: its scenery, character, &c |volume=1 |publisher=George Routledge and Sons |year=1877 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=oncIAAAAQAAJ&pg=PA142 |page=142}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=carleton-rocky>{{cite book|ref=harv|last=Carleton |first=Will |authorlink=Will Carleton |title=Will. Carleton's \"Dandy Pat\" Songster: Being a Choice Collection of Songs |publisher=Dick and Fitzgerald |year=1866 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ULo-AQAAMAAJ&pg=PA62 |pages=59\u201363}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=crowley>{{cite journal|ref=harv|last=Carleton |first=William |authorlink=William Carleton |title=James Joyce: Here Comes Everyword |journal=Manchester Memoirs |volume=133 |publisher=[[Manchester Literary and Philosophical Society]] |year=1996 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=z3weAQAAIAAJ |page=75}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=dibdin-shelaly>{{cite book|ref=harv|last=Dibdin|first=Charles Isaac Mungo |authorlink=Charles Isaac Mungo Dibdin |title=The Twig of Shelaly |work=Mirth and metre: consisting of poems [&c.]. |publisher=Vernor, Hood, & Sharpe |year=1807 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=3yNYAAAAcAAJ&pg=PA86 |pages=85\u201387}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=dict-dolan>{{cite dictionary|ref=harv|last=Dolan |first=Terence Patrick |title=shillelagh |dictionary=A Dictionary of Hiberno-English: The Irish Use of English |publisher=[[Gill & Macmillan]] |year=2006 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=RN0p1uienWMC&pg=PA209 |page=209|isbn=9780717140398 }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=hall>{{cite book|ref=harv|last=Hall |first=Mrs. S. C. |authorlink=Mrs. S. C. Hall |title=Traits and stories of the Irish peasantry |publisher=|year=1841 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Ev-IOz-9ruAC&pg=PA426 |page=426 note}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=irish-times>{{cite journal|author=Y |authorlink= |title=How Black Is A Blackthorn? |newspaper=The Irish Times |date=24 February 2000 |url=https://www.irishtimes.com/opinion/how-black-is-a-blackthorn-1.248616}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=james>{{cite book|ref=harv|last=James |first=Peter |authorlink=<!--Peter James--> |title=Warehouse Eyes: the Albums of Bob Dylan |publisher=Lulu.com |year=2006 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=2BucuSs84UkC&pg=PA248 |page=248|isbn=9781411680845 }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=mabey>{{cite book|ref=harv|last=Mabey|first=Richard |authorlink=Richard Mabey |title=Plantcraft: a guide to the everyday use of wild plants  |publisher=Universe Books |year=1978 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=8lxnAAAAMAAJ |page=43|isbn=9780801841903}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=mccann>{{cite book|ref=harv|last=McCann |first=Sean |authorlink=Sean McCann (actor)|title=The Fighting Irish - |publisher=Leslie Frewin |year=1972 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=jT-CAAAAIAAJ |page=153}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=mchugh>{{cite book|ref=harv|last=McHugh |first=Roland |authorlink=<!--Roland McHugh-->|title=Annotations to Finnegans wake |publisher=Johns Hopkins University Press |year=1991|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=8lxnAAAAMAAJ |page=361|isbn=9780801841903 }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=wright>{{cite book|ref=harv|last=Wright |first=William|authorlink=s:Wright, William (1837-1899) (DNB00) <!--William Wright (1837\u20131899)--> |title=The Bront\u00ebs in Ireland: Or, Facts Stranger Than Fiction |year=1893|publisher=[[Pavilion Books]] |url=https://archive.org/details/brontsinireland01wriggoog |pages=[https://archive.org/details/brontsinireland01wriggoog/page/n302 283]\u2013285}}</ref>\n\n}}\n\n===Sources===\n{{Commons category|Shillelagh}}\n{{Refbegin}}\n*{{cite book|ref=harv|last=Colum |first=Padraic |authorlink=Padraic Colum |title=A Treasury of Irish Folklore |publisher=Kilkenny Press |year=1988 |url=https://books.google.com/books?isbn=0517676125 |pages=397\u2013399}}\n*{{cite book|ref=harv|last=Hurley |first=John W. |title=Shillelagh: The Irish Fighting Stick |publisher=Caravat Press |year=2007 |isbn=978-1-4303-2570-3 | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ZrFMHmsMmWAC}}\n*{{cite book|ref=harv|last=O'Donnell |first=Patrick Denis |authorlink=Patrick Denis O'Donnell |title=The Irish Factions Fighters of the 19th Century |publisher=Anvil Books |year=1975 | url=https://books.google.ie/books/about/The_Irish_Faction_Fighters_of_the_19th_C.html?id=sJbaAAAAMAAJ}}\n{{Refend}}\n\n[[Category:Clubs (weapon)]]\n[[Category:Primitive weapons]]\n[[Category:Ritual weapons]]\n[[Category:Irish folklore]]\n[[Category:Fashion accessories]]\n", "text_old": "{{For|other things called \"shillelagh\"|Shillelagh (disambiguation)}}\n{{EngvarB|date=February 2018}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2018}}\n[[File:Assorted shillelagh.JPG|thumb|right|Assorted shillelaghs.]]\nA '''shillelagh''' ({{IPAc-en|\u0283|\u1d7b|\u02c8|l|e\u026a|l|i}} {{respell|shi|LAY|lee}} or {{IPAc-en|\u0283|\u1d7b|\u02c8|l|e\u026a|l|\u0259}} {{respell|shi|LAY|l\u0259}}; {{lang-ga|sail \u00e9ille}} or {{lang|ga|saill \u00e9alaigh}}<ref name=barry/> {{IPA-ga|\u02c8sal\u02b2 \u02c8e\u02d0l\u0320\u02b2\u0259|}}, \"thonged willow\") is a wooden walking stick and [[Club (weapon)|club or cudgel]], typically made from a stout knotty [[blackthorn]] stick with a large knob at the top.  It is associated with Ireland and [[Irish mythology|Irish folklore]].\n\nOther spelling variants include '''shillelah''', '''shillalah''', and '''shillaly'''.\n\n== Etymology ==\nThe name shillelagh is the [[Hiberno-English]] [[Corruption (linguistics)|corruption]] of the Irish (Gaelic) form {{lang|ga|sail \u00e9ille}}, where {{lang|ga|sail}} means \"willow\" or \"cudgel\" and {{lang|ga|\u00e9ille}} is [[genitive]] for {{lang|ga|iall}} meaning \"thong\", \"strap\", \"leash\", \"string\", etc.{{sfnp|Hurley|2007|p=121}}<ref name=dict-dolan/>\n\nAs an alternate etymology, [[Mrs. S. C. Hall]] as well as [[P. W. Joyce]] have written that the name may have derived from the wood being sourced from forest land in the village or [[Barony (Ireland)|barony]] of [[Shillelagh (barony)|Shillelagh, County Wicklow]].  The geographic name Shillelagh derives from {{lang|ga|S\u00edol \u00c9alaigh}}\u3000\"Descendants of \u00c9alach\".<ref name=hall/>{{sfnp|Hurley|2007|p=119}}<ref>[http://www.oed.com/view/Entry/178130?redirectedFrom=shillelagh#eid Oxford English Dictionary]: Etymology: < the name of a barony and village in Co. Wicklow. OED provides the following quotation: \"1785 F. Grose ''Classical Dict. Vulgar Tongue'', ''Shillaley'', an oaken sapling, or cudgel, (Irish) from a wood of that name famous for its oaks.\"</ref><ref>[http://www.etymonline.com/index.php?term=shillelagh Online Etymology Dictionary]: ''shillelagh'' 1772, \"cudgel,\" earlier, \"oak wood used to make cudgels\" (1670s), from ''Shillelagh'', town and barony in Co. Wicklow, Ireland, famous for its oaks.</ref>\n\n== Construction ==\nShillelaghs are traditionally made from [[blackthorn]] (sloe) wood (''Prunus spinosa'') or oak.<ref name=\"chouinard\">{{cite journal |last1=Chouinard B.A. |first1=Maxime |title=The stick is king: The Shillelagh Bata or the rediscovery of a living Irish martial tradition |url=http://www.freifechter.com/files/stick_edited.pdf |accessdate=5 July 2011 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120302040109/http://www.freifechter.com/files/stick_edited.pdf |archivedate=2012-03-02}}; [http://cimande.com/blackthorn/pdf/stick_edited.pdf copy].</ref> With the scarcity of oak in Ireland the term came increasingly to denote a blackthorn stick,{{sfnp|Colum|1988|p=397}} and indeed '''blackthorn stick''' is sometimes glossed as equivalent to shillelagh.<ref name=mchugh/><ref name=mabey/>\n\nWood from the root was prized since this would be used for the knob,<ref name=\"chouinard\"/> and was less prone to crack or break during use.\n\n=== Curing and polishing ===\nMost commonly, the chosen wood would be placed up a chimney to cure for a duration of several months to several years;{{Refn|group=lower-alpha|The stick may be smeared with butter <!--or lard (no ref)--> before being hung in the chimney, as a preparatory step.<ref name=hall/>}} the accumulated layer of [[soot]] gave the shillelagh its typical black shiny appearance.<ref name=hall/><ref name=\"chouinard\"/>\n\nThe less frequent methods were to bury the shank in a dung pile, or even in [[Calcium hydroxide|slack lime]].<ref name=hall/><!--for roughly the same amount of time.--> The stick may require protection from its dung bath by being wrapped in well-greased oiled brown paper (steeped in hog's lard or oil).<ref name=carleton/>\n\nBoth of the previous methods would be finished with oils or sealants, etc. A further coat of special soot finish may be applied,<ref name=\"chouinard\"/> or a mixture of [[Graphite|black lead]] and grease rubbed on with woolen cloth to a polishing finish.<ref name=carleton/> Some examples may just be given a coat of black paint.<ref name=irish-times/>\n\nRarer still was [[brining]], where the shank was placed into a basin of saltwater. The saltwater, being a hypertonic solution, would pull moisture from the shank with little warping.{{cn|date=July 2019}} One isolated case of this brining method being used, by [[Charlotte Bront\u00eb]]'s uncle named Hugh, has been documented. Hugh Bront\u00eb is said to have rubbed train oil ([[whale oil]]) on the stick using [[chamois leather]], and applied [[magpie]] blood to give it a darker appearance.<ref name=wright/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://hemamisfits.com/2014/06/09/shillelaghs/ |last=Chouinard |first=Maxime |title=Shillelaghs |date=9 June 2014}}</ref>\n\n=== Dimensions ===\n[[File:Shillelaghs in various stages of completion.jpg|thumb|Oaken shillelaghs in various stages of completion]]\n\nThey are commonly the length of a walking stick (distance from the floor to one's wrist with elbow slightly bent),{{cn|date=July 2019}} or rather longer, about 4 feet or 5 feet, as opposed to the walking stick measuring about 3 feet.{{sfnp|Hurley|2007|pp=144, 157}} In the broad sense, the Shillealagh ''bata'' or sticks could include short mallets only 1 \u2013 2 feet long to long poles 6 \u2013 9 feet.<ref name=\"chouinard\"/>\n\n=== Fittings ===\nShillelaghs may be hollowed at the heavy \"hitting\" end and filled with molten lead to increase the weight beyond the typical two pounds; this sort of shillelagh is known as a 'loaded stick'.{{Refn|group=\"lower-alpha\"|These loaded versions are called by such names as ''smacht\u00edn''\u3000(''smacht\u00edn ceann luaidhe'' or \"lead-headed cudgel\"), and are the size of smaller ''ailp\u00edn''.{{sfnp|Hurley|2007|p=148}}}}<ref name=\"chouinard\"/>{{sfnp|Hurley|2007|p=148}}\n\nThe loaded types needed to have its knob fitted with iron [[ferrules]] to maintain structural integrity.{{sfnp|Hurley|2007|p=148}} But the sticks also got iron ferrules fitted onto its narrow end as well.<ref name=\"wright\"/>{{sfnp|Hurley|2007|p=145}}<ref name=\"chouinard\"/> Shillelagh may also have a heavy knob for a handle which can be used for striking.{{sfnp|Colum|1988|p=397}}<!--as well as parrying and disarming an opponent. (no book source found; Keelly &Rogers (1999) ''How to be Irish'' suggests the opposite: \"knob end was employed to strike, and the other end to parry\") --> Shillelaghs may also have a strap attached, similar to commercially made walking sticks, to place around the holder's wrist.<ref name=mccann/>\n\n== History ==\n\nThe shillelagh was originally used for settling disputes in a gentlemanly manner \u2014 like a duel with pistols or swords. Modern practitioners of [[bataireacht]] study the use of the shillelagh for self-defense and as a [[martial art]]. Of the practice, researcher J. W. Hurley writes:\n\n<blockquote>\nMethods of shillelagh fighting have evolved over a period of thousands of years, from the spear, staff, axe and sword fighting of the Irish. There is some evidence which suggests that the use of Irish stick weapons may have evolved in a progression from a reliance on long spears and [[wattles]], to shorter spears and wattles, to the shillelagh, alpeen,{{Refn|group=\"lower-alpha\"|There is only a vague distinction between shillelagh and alpeen (Diarmaid \u00d3 Muirithe), though the alpeen may be longer or heavier, and be knobbed in the minds of some ([[P. W. Joyce]]).{{sfnp|Hurley|2007|p=131}} An ''alpeen'' or ''ailpeen'' ({{lang-ga|ailp\u00edn}}) is glossed as. \"thick [[alpenstock]]\", \"[[walking stick#Types|ashplant]]\", \"club\", \"heavy stick\".<ref>{{harvp|Dolan|2006}} \"ailpeen, alpeen\", ''Dictionary of Hiberno-English'', pp. 5\u20136.</ref>}} blackthorn (walking-stick) and short cudgel. By the 19th century Irish shillelagh-fighting had evolved into a practice which involved the use of three basic types of weapons, sticks which were long, medium or short in length.{{sfnp|Hurley|2007|p=347}}</blockquote>\n\n== Folklore and balladry ==\nShillelaghs are sometimes referred to in a similar context in folk songs. In the ballad \"[[Finnegan's Wake]]\" occurs the phrase \"Shillelagh law did all engage\", signifying that a brawl has broken out;<ref name=crowley/> \"shillelagh law\" itself has been explained as meaning the accepted rule governing the usage of the weapon.{{sfnp|Hurley|2007|p=11}}\n\nThe anti-recruiting folk song \"[[Arthur McBride]]\", where the recruiters are struck with a shillelagh,<ref name=bonnie/><ref name=james/> and in the 19th century song \"[[Rocky Road to Dublin]]\", in which references are made to fashioning a shillelagh (\"I cut a stout blackthorn\"), and using it (\"shillalah\"<ref name=carleton-rocky/>) to hold a tied bag over one's shoulder, and using it as a striking weapon.<ref name=bonnie-rocky/>\n\n[[Charles Dibdin the younger]] wrote a song entitled \"The Twig of Shelaly\",<ref name=dibdin-shelaly/> later reprinted as \"The Twig of Shillelah\".<ref name=albion/>\n\n== Modern usage ==\n[[Image:Jeweledshillelagh.jpg|thumb|right|The Jeweled Shillelagh]]\nThe shillelegah came to be regarded as a stereotypical symbol of Irishness in popular culture,{{sfnp|Hurley|2007|p=15}} particularly in an Irish-American context.\n\nMembers of a number of [[Irish_in_the_British_Armed_Forces#Regiments|Irish regiments in the British Armed Forces]] have traditionally carried Blackthorn sticks, including officers of the [[Irish Guards]].<ref name=\"matusitz2014\">{{cite book |title = Symbolism in Terrorism: Motivation, Communication, and Behavior | last = Matusitz |first= Jonathan | publisher = Rowman & Littlefield | year = 2014 | page = 208 | isbn = 9781442235793 | quote = More recently, the MGM-51 antitank missile [..] was baptized as the \"Shillelagh\". Officers of the Irish Guards are given shillelaghs upon graduation - just like Irish Regiments of the British Army in the past }}</ref> Officers of the [[69th Infantry Regiment (New York)|Fighting 69th]] regiment of the United States [[Army National Guard]] also carry shillelaghs as rank badges in parades.<ref>{{cite web | title=Green Camouflage and Purple Hearts | author=Alan Feuer | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2005/03/18/nyregion/18fighting.html| work=[[The New York Times]] | date=18 March 2005 | accessdate=6 October 2008}}</ref> \n\nIn sports, the [[Boston Celtics]] logo has a [[leprechaun]] leaning on his shillelagh, and it also features with the leprechaun on some logos of [[Confraternity of Brothers Clubs|Brothers]] [[Rugby league]] teams in Australia. In San Diego, [[San Diego Padres|Padres]] broadcaster [[Mark Andrew Grant|Mark Grant]] popularised the shillelagh as a rally call, by using terms like \"Shillelagh Power\" to describe late game heroics by the Padres. The success of the phrase led the San Diego Padres store to carry [[inflatable]] shillelaghs. Similarly, in the [[college football|college games of American football]], a [[Jeweled Shillelagh]] is the trophy given to the winner of the [[college rivalry|rivalry game]] between the [[USC Trojans]] and [[Notre Dame Fighting Irish]]. Professional wrestler [[Dave Finlay|Finlay]] carried a shillelagh to the ring in December 2006 as an \"illegal weapon\".{{fact|date=December 2019}}\n\nA number of items take their name from the shillelegah, including the [[MGM-51 Shillelagh]] anti-tank missile,<ref name=\"matusitz2014\"/> and several aircraft of the [[357th Fighter Group]] which were named for the club, and had similar representative nose art.{{fact|date=July 2019}} In the tabletop game [[Dungeons and Dragons]], 'shillelagh' is a low-level spell used by casters to make simple clubs into powerful bludgeoning weapons.<ref>{{cite book | last=Dungeons & Dragons | title=Player's Handbook | url=http://dnd.wizards.com/products/tabletop-games/rpg-products/rpg_playershandbook | edition=5e | publisher=[[Wizards of the Coast]] | year=2014 | isbn=978-0-7869-6560-1 }}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Rungu (weapon)]] - a similar club common in East Africa.\n* [[Knobkierie]] - similar club associated with Southern Africa and [[World War I]] British troops.\n* [[Sgian-dubh]] - \"black knife\" of Scottish Highland attire\n\n== Explanatory notes ==\n{{notelist}}\n\n== References ==\n===Notes===\n{{Reflist|30em|refs=\n<ref name=albion>{{cite book|ref=harv|last=Dibdin|first=C., Jr. |authorlink=Charles Isaac Mungo Dibdin |title=The Twig of Shillelah |work=The Pride of Albion. A Collection of New and Pleasing Songs, Etc |publisher=T. Hughes |year=1810 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=zzVYAAAAcAAJ&pg=PA126 |pages=12\u201387}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=barry>{{cite book|ref=harv|last=Barry |first=Michael |authorlink=<!--Michael Barry (Irish writer)--> |title=Dublin's Strangest Tales: Extraordinary but true stories |publisher=[[Pavilion Books]] |year=2013 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=IrO_CAAAQBAJ&pg=PT9 |page=9|isbn=9781909396449 }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=bonnie>{{cite book|last1=Milner |first1=Dan |authorlink1=Dan Milner |last2=Kaplan  |first2=Paul |authorlink2=<!--Paul Kaplan--> |title=Arthur McBride |work=Songs of England, Ireland, and Scotland: A Bonnie Bunch of Roses  |location=|publisher=Oak Publications |year=1983 |isbn=1-783234-92-X |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ZpbIDgAAQBAJ&pg=PT87 |pages=87\u201388}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=bonnie-rocky>{{cite book|last1=Milner |first1=Dan |authorlink1=Dan Milner |last2=Kaplan  |first2=Paul |authorlink2=<!--Paul Kaplan--> |title=The Rocky Road to Dublin |work=Songs of England, Ireland, and Scotland: A Bonnie Bunch of Roses  |location=|publisher=Oak Publications |year=1983 |isbn=1-783234-92-X |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ZpbIDgAAQBAJ&pg=PT58|pages=58\u201359}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=carleton>{{cite book|ref=harv|last=Carleton |first=William |authorlink=William Carleton |title=Ireland: its scenery, character, &c |volume=1 |publisher=George Routledge and Sons |year=1877 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=oncIAAAAQAAJ&pg=PA142 |page=142}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=carleton-rocky>{{cite book|ref=harv|last=Carleton |first=Will |authorlink=Will Carleton |title=Will. Carleton's \"Dandy Pat\" Songster: Being a Choice Collection of Songs |publisher=Dick and Fitzgerald |year=1866 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ULo-AQAAMAAJ&pg=PA62 |pages=59\u201363}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=crowley>{{cite journal|ref=harv|last=Carleton |first=William |authorlink=William Carleton |title=James Joyce: Here Comes Everyword |journal=Manchester Memoirs |volume=133 |publisher=[[Manchester Literary and Philosophical Society]] |year=1996 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=z3weAQAAIAAJ |page=75}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=dibdin-shelaly>{{cite book|ref=harv|last=Dibdin|first=Charles Isaac Mungo |authorlink=Charles Isaac Mungo Dibdin |title=The Twig of Shelaly |work=Mirth and metre: consisting of poems [&c.]. |publisher=Vernor, Hood, & Sharpe |year=1807 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=3yNYAAAAcAAJ&pg=PA86 |pages=85\u201387}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=dict-dolan>{{cite dictionary|ref=harv|last=Dolan |first=Terence Patrick |title=shillelagh |dictionary=A Dictionary of Hiberno-English: The Irish Use of English |publishe